# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baseball-prospectus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] It started as an addition to the *Idol* format that was based on *Pop Idol* from British television, and it became one of the most successful shows in the history of American television.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The concept of the series involves discovering recording stars from unsigned singing talents, with the winner determined by American viewers using phones, Internet platforms, and SMS text voting.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The success of *American Idol* has been described as "unparalleled in broadcasting history".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] A rival TV executive said the series was "the most impactful show in the history of television".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] It became a recognized springboard for launching the career of many artists as bona fide stars.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In 2001, Fuller, Cowell, and TV producer Simon Jones attempted to sell the *Pop Idol* format to the United States, but the idea was initially met with poor responses from all the television networks including UPN and Fox.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] However, Rupert Murdoch, head of Fox's parent company, was later persuaded to buy the series by his daughter, Elisabeth, who had seen the British show.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Although Fox's executives wanted to change the format, Murdoch insisted that it should remain the same as the British one.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] One change was nevertheless made due to the presence of multiple time zones in the United States that made it impractical for the country to vote in the same time period, an additional half-hour results show was therefore added the day following the performance show.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The show was renamed *American Idol: The Search for a Superstar* and debuted in the summer of 2002.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Cowell was initially offered the job of showrunner but turned down the offer; Lythgoe then took over that position.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Much to the surprise of Cowell and Fox, it became one of the biggest shows of the summer.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] With its successful launch in the summer, the show was then moved to January and expanded.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The show grew into a phenomenon largely due to its personal engagement with the contestants by prompting the viewers to vote, and the presence of the acid-tongued Cowell as a judge.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] By 2004, it had become the most-watched show on American television, a position it then held for seven consecutive seasons until 2011.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] However, after a few years of sharp declining ratings starting in 2012, with rating falls of over 20% each season, the fifteenth season would be its last on Fox, ending its run in April 2016.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In May 2017, ABC acquired the rights to the series and the program returned for the 2017–18 television season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The first season of the revived series, or the sixteenth season overall, started airing in March 2018.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Eight seasons have been aired on ABC as of May 2025.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The show had originally planned on having four judges following the *Pop Idol* format; however, only three judges had been found by the time of the audition round in the first season, namely Randy Jackson, Paula Abdul, and Simon Cowell.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] A fourth judge, radio DJ Stryker, was originally chosen but he dropped out citing "image concerns." In the second season, New York radio personality Angie Martinez had been hired as a fourth judge but withdrew after only a few days of auditions, due to being uncomfortable with giving out criticism.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The show decided to continue with the three judges format until the eighth season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] All three original judges stayed on the judging panel for eight seasons.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the eighth season, Latin Grammy Award-nominated singer-songwriter and record producer Kara DioGuardi was added as a fourth judge.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Abdul left the show in 2009, after the eighth season, as a result of failing to agree to terms with the show producers.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Emmy Award-winning talk show host Ellen DeGeneres replaced Abdul for the ninth season, but left in 2010 after just one season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] DioGuardi was let go from *American Idol* in 2010 after two seasons, as producers favored a return to the three-person judges panel previously used prior to DioGuardi's appearance on the show.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Cowell also left the show in 2010 to introduce the American version of his show *The X Factor* in 2011.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Jackson was the only judge from the ninth season to return for the tenth.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Jennifer Lopez and Steven Tyler joined the judging panel in the tenth season, but both left in 2012 after two seasons.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Jackson was the only judge from the eleventh season to return for the twelfth.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] They were replaced by three new judges, Mariah Carey, Nicki Minaj, and Keith Urban, who joined Jackson in the twelfth season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] However, both Carey and Minaj left after one season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Jackson also departed the judges table after twelve seasons, but would return as the in-house mentor for the thirteenth season in 2014, after which he left the show permanently.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Urban was the only judge from the twelfth season to return as a judge for the thirteenth season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] After a one-season hiatus, Lopez returned to *American Idol* for the thirteenth season, and was joined by former mentor Harry Connick Jr.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] After this, Lopez, Urban, and Connick Jr. remained on the show until its cancellation after the fifteenth season in 2016.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] When the show was revived by ABC in 2018, Katy Perry, Luke Bryan, and Lionel Richie were selected as judges, marking the sixteenth season of *Idol*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Bryan and Richie have remained on the show since, while Perry left the show in May 2024 after seven seasons.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] On July 31, 2024, published reports announced former *Idol* winner Carrie Underwood as Perry's replacement, joining Bryan and Richie for the twenty-third season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In August 2025, it was announced Bryan, Richie, and Underwood would return as judges for the twenty-fourth season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Guest judges may occasionally be introduced.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the second season, guest judges such as Richie and Gladys Knight were used, and in the third season, Donna Summer, Quentin Tarantino, Gloria Estefan, and some of the mentors also joined as judges to critique the performances in the final rounds.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Guest judges were sporadically used during the audition rounds: Gene Simmons, LL Cool J, Brandy, Mark McGrath, and Kenny Loggins in the fourth season; Carole Bayer Sager, Jewel, and Olivia Newton-John in the sixth season; Shania Twain, Neil Patrick Harris, Avril Lavigne, Mary J.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Blige, Joe Jonas, Kristin Chenoweth, Victoria Beckham, and Perry in the ninth season (substituting in the vacant chair, before DeGeneres was hired); and Adam Lambert filled in for Urban at one audition location during the fourteenth season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the ABC version, two instances occurred during the live shows: Abdul filled in for Bryan on one episode of the nineteenth season, while Alanis Morissette and Ed Sheeran filled in for Perry and Richie on an episode of the twenty-first season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The first season was co-hosted by Ryan Seacrest and Brian Dunkleman, following the format of *Pop Idol* of using two presenters.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Dunkleman quit thereafter, resulting in Seacrest becoming the sole emcee starting with the second season in 2003.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Seacrest has remained as sole host of *American Idol* ever since, with the exception of the two-year hiatus between 2016 and 2018 as well as April 8, 2019, during the seventeenth season, when Bobby Bones subbed for Seacrest after the latter fell ill.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Dunkleman did, however, return for the initial series finale on Fox in 2016 as a guest.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In a series of steps, the show selected the eventual winner out of many tens of thousands of contestants.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The eligible age-range for contestants is fifteen to twenty-eight years old.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The initial age limit was sixteen to twenty-four in the first three seasons, but the upper limit was raised to twenty-eight in the fourth season, and the lower limit was reduced to fifteen in the tenth season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The contestants have to be legal U.S. residents, can not have advanced to particular stages of the competition in previous seasons, and must not have held a current recording or talent representation contract by the semi-final stage (in previous years by the audition stage).
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] For the first eighteen seasons, contestants went through at least three sets of cuts.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The first was a brief audition with a few other contestants in front of selectors which may include one of the show's producers.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Although auditions can exceed 10,000 in each city, only a few hundred of these made it past the preliminary round of auditions.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Successful contestants then sing in front of producers, where more may be cut.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Only then can they proceed to audition in front of the judges, which is the only audition stage shown on television.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Those selected by the judges are sent to Hollywood.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Between 10 and 60 people in each city may make it to Hollywood (the average total is between 150 and 200).
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] From the nineteenth season onwards, contestants request a Zoom interview and audition remotely for the show's producers.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] If the audition goes well, they will then invite the contestants to audition in front of the judges, in one of the audition cities.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Once in Hollywood, the contestants perform individually or in groups in a series of rounds.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Until the tenth season, there were usually three rounds of eliminations in Hollywood.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the first round the contestants emerged in groups but performed individually.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] For the next round, the contestants put themselves in small groups and performed a song together.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the final round, the contestants performed solo with a song of their choice a cappella or accompanied by a band‍—‌depending on the season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the second and third seasons, contestants were also asked to write original lyrics or melody in an additional round after the first round.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the seventh season, the group round was eliminated and contestants may, after a first solo performance and on judges approval, skip a second solo round and move directly to the final Hollywood round.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the twelfth season, the executive producers split up the females and males and chose the members to form the groups in the group round.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the tenth and eleventh seasons, a further round was added in Las Vegas, where the contestants performed in groups based on a theme, followed by one final solo round to determine the semi-finalists.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] At the end of this stage of the competition, 24 to 36 contestants were selected to move on to the semi-final stage.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the twelfth season the Las Vegas round became a Sudden Death round, where the judges had to choose five guys and five girls each night (four nights) to make the top twenty.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the fourteenth season, the "Hollywood or Home" round was dropped, and a Showcase round was added, where the contestants performed at the House of Blues or auditorium for the judges and a live audience, and these performances determine who makes into the Top 24.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the seventeenth and eighteenth seasons, the showcase round took place in Hawaii.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] From the nineteenth season onward, a showstopper round was used.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] From the semi-finals onward, the fate of the contestants is decided by public vote.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] During the contestant's performance as well as the recap at the end, a toll-free telephone number for each contestant was displayed on the screen.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] For a two-hour period after the episode ends (up to four hours for the finale) in each US time zone, viewers may call or send a text message to their preferred contestant's telephone number, and each call or text message was registered as a vote for that contestant.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Viewers were allowed to vote as many times as they can within the two-hour voting window.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] However, the show reserves the right to discard votes by power dialers.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] One or more of the least popular contestants may be eliminated in successive weeks until a winner emerges.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Over 110 million votes were cast in the first season, and by the tenth season the seasonal total had increased to nearly 750 million.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Voting via text messaging was made available in the second season when AT&T Wireless joined as a sponsor of the show, and 7.5 million text messages were sent to *American Idol* that season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The number of text messages rapidly increased, reaching 178 million texts by the eighth season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Online voting was offered for the first time in the tenth season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The votes are counted and verified by Telescope Inc.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the first three seasons, the semi-finalists were split into different groups to perform individually in their respective night.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the first season, there were three groups of ten, with the top three contestants from each group making the finals.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the second and third seasons, there were four groups of eight, and the top two of each selected.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] These seasons also featured a wildcard round, where contestants who failed to qualify were given another chance.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the first season, only one wildcard contestant was chosen by the judges, giving a total of ten finalists.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the second and third seasons, each of the three judges championed one contestant with the public advancing a fourth into the finals, making 12 finalists in all.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] From the fourth through seventh and ninth seasons, the twenty-four semi-finalists were divided by gender in order to ensure an equal gender division in the top twelve.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The men and women sang separately on consecutive nights, and the bottom two in each groups were eliminated each week until only six of each remained to form the top twelve.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The wildcard round returned in the eighth season, wherein there were three groups of twelve, with three contestants moving forward – the highest male, the highest female, and the next highest-placed singer – for each night, and four wildcards were chosen by the judges to produce a final 13.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Starting in tenth season, the girls and boys perform on separate nights.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the tenth and eleventh seasons, five of each gender were chosen, and three wildcards were chosen by the judges to form a final 13.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the twelfth season, the top twenty semifinalists were split into gender groups, with five of each gender advancing to form the final 10.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the thirteenth season, there were thirty semifinalists, but only twenty semifinalists (ten for each gender) were chosen by the judges to perform on the live shows, with five in each gender based on the vote and three wildcards chosen by the judges composing the final 13.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the fourteenth season, the top 24 performed at The Fillmore Detroit, starting with the 12 males on one night and then the 12 females on the next night.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The following week, the same order went for the top 16, with four males eliminated, followed by four females based on the vote.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Then, on the first night of finals, a similar sequence from the thirteenth season was used to determine the final 12, with five of each gender based on the vote and two wildcards chosen by the judges.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the fifteenth season, the top 24 performed at Cathedral of Saint Vibiana in Los Angeles and were split into two groups of twelve and performed twice, one being a solo performance and one being a duet with a former Idol contestant.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In each group, the judges chose 7 contestants to advance to the top 14 where the judges chose 4 to advance to the top 10 and remaining 6 contestants were chosen based on the vote.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the sixteenth season, the top 24 performed at the Academy in the Heart of LA, and the show repeated the process from the previous season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] However, instead of Idol alumnus as duet partners, superstar celebrity singers were used as the duet partners.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the seventeenth season, the same process was repeated again.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] However, instead of a top 24, it's a top 20, the contestants performed at the Wiltern Theatre in Los Angeles, and performed solos in one episode, and performed the duets in two episodes.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the eighteenth season, due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the top 20 performed at their homes, and based on the vote, half of the top 20 would advance to the top 10, and the other half would be eliminated.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] However, a wild card was given to one of the bottom 10 to save them from elimination.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the nineteenth season, the show used a combination of the process from the sixteenth and fourteenth seasons.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the twentieth season, the show repeated the process from the previous season, but they used a top 20 instead of a top 16, and there were no all star duets.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the twenty-first season, the same process was repeated, but they started with a top 26 instead of a top 24.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the twenty-second season, the show repeated the process from the twentieth season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The finals are broadcast in primetime from Los Angeles, in front of a live studio audience (except the eighteenth season, due to the COVID-19 pandemic).
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] From 2002 to 2019 and from 2021 to 2022, the venue was CBS Television City.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Since 2023, the show has been filmed at Red Studios.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The finals lasted eight weeks in the first season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] From the second to ninth and fourteenth seasons, the finals lasted eleven weeks.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The tenth and eleventh seasons lasted for twelve weeks, while the twelfth season lasted for ten weeks.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the thirteenth season, the finals lasted thirteen weeks.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The finals lasted seven weeks in the fifteenth season, and six weeks in the sixteenth season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Each finalist performs songs based on a weekly theme which may be a musical genre such as Motown, disco, or big band, songs by artists such as Michael Jackson, Elvis Presley or The Beatles, or more general themes such as *Billboard* number-one hits or songs from the contestant's year of birth.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Contestants usually worked with a celebrity mentor related to the theme.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] From the tenth to twelfth seasons, Jimmy Iovine was brought in as a mentor for the season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Initially the contestants sang one song each week, but this was increased to two songs from top four or five onwards, then three songs for the top two or three.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The most popular contestants are usually not revealed in the results show.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Instead, typically the three contestants (two in later rounds) who received the lowest number of votes was called to the center of the stage.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] One of these three was usually sent to safety; however the two remaining were not necessarily the bottom two.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The contestant with the fewest votes was then revealed and eliminated from the competition.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] A montage of the eliminated contestant's time on the show was played and they gave their final performance (from the fourteenth season onward, the montage and the final performance were dropped).
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] However, in the sixth season, during the series' first ever Idol Gives Back episode, no contestant was eliminated, but on the following week, two were sent home.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Moreover, from the eighth to the fourteenth seasons, and the seventeenth season onward, the judges may overturn viewers' decision with a "Judges' Save" if they unanimously agreed to.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] "The save" could only be used once, and only up through the Top 5.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the eighth to tenth and fourteenth seasons, a double elimination then took place in the week following the activation of the save, but in the eleventh and thirteenth seasons, a regular single elimination took place.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The save was not activated in the twelfth season and consequently, a non-elimination took place in the week after its expiration with the votes then carrying over into the following week.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The "Fan Save" was introduced in the fourteenth season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] During the finals, viewers were given a five-minute window to vote for the contestants in danger of elimination by using their Twitter account to decide which contestant will move on to the next show, starting with the Top 8.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] During the original run of *American Idol* on Fox, the finale week consisted of a one-hour long final performance night and a two-hour last episode of the season that culminates in revealing the winner, both of which are broadcast live in the U.S.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] For the first, third through sixth and fourteenth through fifteenth seasons it was broadcast from the Dolby Theatre, which has an audience capacity of approximately 3,400.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The second-season finale took place at the Gibson Amphitheatre, which had an audience capacity of over 6,000.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the seventh through thirteenth seasons, the venue was at the Nokia Theatre L.A.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Live, which holds an audience of over 7,000.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The eighteenth-season finale was conducted virtually due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] The winner usually receives a record deal with a major label, which may be for up to six albums, and secures a management contract with *American Idol*-affiliated 19 Management (which has the right of first refusal to sign all contestants), as well as various lucrative contracts.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] All winners prior to the ninth season reportedly earned at least $1 million in their first year as winner.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] At first the contract came with a $250,000-plus advance, but dropped to about $62,500 over the Fox years.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] All the runners-up of the first ten seasons, as well as some of other finalists, had also received record deals with major labels.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] However, starting in the eleventh season, the runner-up may only be guaranteed a single-only deal.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] BMG/Sony (first through ninth seasons), UMG (tenth through fifteenth seasons), and Disney Music Group's Hollywood Records (sixteenth through eighteenth seasons) had the right of first refusal to sign contestants for three months after the season's finale.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] In the fourteenth and fifteenth seasons, the winner was signed with Big Machine Records.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] Prominent music mogul Clive Davis also produced some of the selected contestants' albums, such as Kelly Clarkson, Clay Aiken, Fantasia Barrino and Diana DeGarmo.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p01] All top 10 (11 in the tenth and twelfth seasons, 5 in the fourteenth season, and 7 in the sixteenth season) finalists earn the privilege of going on a tour, where the participants may each earn a six-figure sum.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Each season premieres with the audition round, taking place in different cities.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The audition episodes typically feature a mix of potential finalists, interesting characters and woefully inadequate contestants.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Each successful contestant receives a golden or platinum ticket to proceed on to the next round in Hollywood.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Based on their performances during the Hollywood round (Las Vegas round from the tenth through twelfth seasons), 24 to 36 contestants are selected by the judges to participate in the semifinals.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] From the semifinals onward the contestants perform their songs live, with the judges making their critiques after each performance.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The contestants are voted for by the viewing public, and the outcome of the public votes is then revealed during a results segment.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The results segment feature group performances by the contestants as well as guest performers.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The Top-three results also features homecoming events for the Top 3 finalists.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The season reaches its climax in a two-hour results finale show, where the winner of the season is revealed.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] With the exception of the first two seasons, the contestants in the semifinals onward perform in front of a studio audience.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] They perform with a full band in the finals.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The current musical director is Kris Pooley, who has been with the show since the sixteenth season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] In previous seasons, the *American Idol* band was led by Rickey Minor (fourth through ninth and thirteenth through fifteenth seasons) and Ray Chew (tenth through twelfth seasons).
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Assistance has also been given by vocal coaches and song arrangers, such as Michael Orland and Debra Byrd to contestants behind the scene.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Starting with the seventh season, contestants may perform with a musical instrument from the Hollywood rounds onward.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] In later seasons, the contestants were allowed to perform with a musical instrument in the auditions.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] During the first nine seasons, performances were usually aired live on Tuesday nights, followed by the results shows on Wednesdays, but moved to Wednesdays and Thursdays from the tenth through thirteenth seasons, with the tenth, eleventh and thirteenth-season finales aired on Tuesday and Wednesday.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] From the fourteenth season onward, there were no separate results shows.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On the fourteenth season, the show aired on Wednesday nights, and on the fifteenth season, Thursday nights.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Since the sixteenth season, the show has been airing on Sundays and Mondays.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The first season of *American Idol* debuted as a summer replacement show in June 2002 on the Fox network.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] It was co-hosted by Ryan Seacrest and Brian Dunkleman.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Randy Jackson, Paula Abdul, and Simon Cowell served as judges.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] In the audition rounds, 121 contestants were selected from around 10,000 who attended the auditions.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] These were cut to 30 for the semifinal, with ten going on to the finals.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] One semifinalist, Delano Cagnolatti, was disqualified for lying to evade the show's age limit.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] One of the early favorites, Tamyra Gray, was eliminated at the top four, the first of several such shock eliminations that were to be repeated in later seasons.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Christina Christian was hospitalized before the top six result show due to chest pains and palpitations, and she was eliminated while she was in the hospital.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Jim Verraros was the first openly gay contestant on the show; his sexual orientation was revealed on his blog, however it was removed during the competition after a request from the show producers over concerns that it might be unfairly influencing votes.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The final showdown was between Justin Guarini, one of the early favorites, and Kelly Clarkson.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Clarkson was not initially thought of as a contender, but impressed the judges with some good performances in the final rounds, such as her performance of Aretha Franklin's "Natural Woman", and Betty Hutton's "Stuff Like That There", and eventually won the crown on September 4, 2002.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] In what was to become a tradition, Clarkson performed the coronation song during the finale, and released the song immediately after the season ended.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The single, "A Moment Like This", went on to break a 38-year-old record held by The Beatles for the biggest leap to number one on the *Billboard* Hot 100.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Guarini did not release any song immediately after the show and remains the only runner-up not to do so.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Both Clarkson and Guarini made a musical film, *From Justin to Kelly*, which was released in 2003 but was widely panned.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Clarkson has since become one of the most successful *Idol* contestants internationally, with worldwide album sales of more than 25 million.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Starting September 30, 2006, this season was repackaged as "*American Idol Rewind*" and syndicated directly to stations in the U.S.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Following the success of the first season, the second season was moved up to air in January 2003.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The number of episodes increased, as did the show's budget and the charge for commercial spots.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Dunkleman left the show, leaving Ryan Seacrest as the lone host.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Randy Jackson, Paula Abdul, and Simon Cowell returned as judges.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Kristin Adams was a correspondent for this season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Corey Clark was disqualified during the finals for having an undisclosed police record; however, he later alleged that he and Paula Abdul had an affair while on the show and that this contributed to his expulsion.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Clark also claimed that Abdul gave him preferential treatment on the show due to their affair.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The allegations were dismissed by Fox after an independent investigation.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Two semi-finalists were also disqualified that year – Jaered Andrews for an arrest on an assault charge, and Frenchie Davis for having previously modeled for an adult website.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The season finale drew more than 38 million viewers, marking *Idol'*s biggest audience ever for a single episode.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Ruben Studdard emerged as the winner, beating Clay Aiken by a small margin.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Out of a total of 24 million votes, Studdard finished just 134,000 votes ahead of Aiken.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] This slim margin of victory was controversial due to the large number of calls that failed to get through.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] In an interview prior to the fifth season, executive producer Nigel Lythgoe indicated that Aiken had led the fan voting from the wildcard week onward until the finale.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Both finalists found success after the show, but Aiken out-performed Studdard's coronation song "Flying Without Wings" with his single release from the show "This Is the Night", as well as in their subsequent album releases.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The fourth-place finisher Josh Gracin also enjoyed some success as a country singer.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The third season premiered on January 19, 2004.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Ryan Seacrest returned as host, and Randy Jackson, Paula Abdul, and Simon Cowell returned as judges.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] One of the most talked-about contestants during the audition process was William Hung whose off-key rendition of Ricky Martin's "She Bangs" received widespread attention.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] His exposure on *Idol* landed him a record deal and surprisingly he became the third bestselling singer from that season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Much media attention on the season had been focused on the three black singers, Fantasia Barrino, LaToya London, and Jennifer Hudson, dubbed the Three Divas.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] All three unexpectedly landed on the bottom three on the top seven result show, with Hudson controversially eliminated.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Elton John, who was one of the mentors that season, called the results of the votes "incredibly racist".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The prolonged stays of John Stevens and Jasmine Trias in the finals, despite negative comments from the judges, had aroused resentment, so much so that John Stevens reportedly received a death threat, which he dismissed as a joke 'blown out of proportion'.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The performance of "Summertime" by Barrino, later known simply as "Fantasia", at Top 8 was widely praised, and Simon Cowell considered it as his favorite *Idol* moment in the nine seasons he was on the show.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Fantasia and Diana DeGarmo were the last two finalists, and Fantasia was crowned as the winner.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Fantasia released as her coronation single "I Believe", a song co-written by the first season finalist Tamyra Gray, and DeGarmo released "Dreams".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The fourth season premiered on January 18, 2005.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] This was the first full season of the series to be aired in high definition; the finale of the third season was also aired in high definition.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The number of those attending the auditions by now had increased to over 100,000 from the 10,000 of the first season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The age limit was raised to 28 in this season, and among those who benefited from this new rule were Constantine Maroulis and Bo Bice, the two rockers of the show.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The top 12 finalists originally included Mario Vazquez, but he dropped out citing 'personal reasons' and was replaced by Nikko Smith.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Later, an employee of Fremantle Media, which produces the show, sued the company for wrongful termination, claiming that he was dismissed after complaining about lewd behavior by Vazquez toward him during the show.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] During the top 11 week, due to a mix-up with the contestants' telephone number, voting was repeated on what was normally the result night, with the result reveal postponed until the following night.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] In May 2005, Underwood was announced the winner, with Bice the runner-up.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Both Underwood and Bice released the coronation song "Inside Your Heaven", with Underwood's version of the song making her the first country artist ever to debut at number-one on the *Billboard* Hot 100 chart.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] As of 2015, Underwood has become the most successful *Idol* contestant in the U.S., selling 16 million albums in the country, while selling a total of 65 million records worldwide.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The fifth season began on January 17, 2006.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] It remains the highest-rated season in the show's run so far.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Two of the more prominent contestants during the Hollywood round were the Brittenum twins who were later disqualified for identity theft.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Chris Daughtry's performance of Fuel's "Hemorrhage (In My Hands)" on the show was widely praised and led to an invitation to join the band as Fuel's new lead singer, an invitation he declined.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] His performance of Live's version of "I Walk the Line" was well received by the judges but later criticized in some quarters for not crediting the arrangement to Live.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] He was eliminated at the top four in a shocking result.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 30, 2006, Taylor Hicks was named *American Idol*, with Katharine McPhee the runner-up.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] "Do I Make You Proud" was released as Hicks' first single and McPhee's was "My Destiny".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Despite being eliminated earlier in the season, Chris Daughtry (as lead of the band Daughtry) became the most successful recording artist from this season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Other contestants, such as Hicks, McPhee, Bucky Covington, Mandisa, Kellie Pickler, and Elliott Yamin have had varying levels of success.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The sixth season began on Tuesday, January 16, 2007.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The premiere drew a massive audience of 37.3 million viewers, peaking in the last half hour with more than 41 million viewers.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Teenager Sanjaya Malakar was the season's most talked-about contestant for his unusual hairdo, and for managing to survive elimination for many weeks due in part to the weblog Vote for the Worst and satellite radio personality Howard Stern, who both encouraged fans to vote for him.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] However, on the Top 7 results, Sanjaya was voted off.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] This season saw the first *Idol Gives Back* telethon-inspired event, which raised more than $76 million in corporate and viewer donations.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] No contestant was eliminated that week, but two (Phil Stacey and Chris Richardson) were eliminated the next.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] In the May 23 season finale, Jordin Sparks was declared the winner with the runner-up being Blake Lewis.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Sparks has had some success as a recording artist post-*Idol*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] This season also saw the launch of the *American Idol* Songwriter contest which allows fans to vote for the "coronation song".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Thousands of recordings of original songs were submitted by songwriters, and 20 entries selected for the public vote.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The winning song, "This Is My Now", was performed by both finalists during the finale and released by Sparks on May 24, 2007.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The seventh season premiered on January 15, 2008, for a two-day, four-hour premiere.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The media focused on the professional status of the seventh season contestants, the so-called 'ringers', many of whom, including Kristy Lee Cook, Brooke White, Michael Johns, and in particular Carly Smithson, had prior recording contracts.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Contestant David Hernandez also attracted some attention due to his past employment as a stripper.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] For the finals, *American Idol* debuted a new state-of-the-art set and stage on March 11, 2008, along with a new on-air look.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] David Cook's performance of "Billie Jean" on top-ten night was lauded by the judges, but provoked controversy when they apparently mistook the Chris Cornell arrangement to be David Cook's own even though the performance was introduced as Cornell's version.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Cornell himself said he was 'flattered' and praised David Cook's performance.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] David Cook was taken to the hospital after the top-nine performance show due to heart palpitations and high blood pressure.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] David Archuleta's performance of John Lennon's "Imagine" was considered by many as one of the best of the season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Jennifer Lopez, who was brought in as a judge in the tenth season, called it a beautiful song-moment that she will never forget.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Jason Castro's semi-final performance of "Hallelujah" also received considerable attention, and it propelled Jeff Buckley's version of the song to the top of the *Billboard* digital song chart.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] This was the first season in which contestants' recordings were released onto iTunes after their performances, and although sales information was not released so as not to prejudice the contest, leaked information indicated that contestants' songs frequently reached the top of iTunes sales charts.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] David Cook was announced the winner on May 21, 2008, the first rocker to win the show.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Both Cook and Archuleta had some success as recording artists with both selling over a million albums in the U.S.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The *American Idol* Songwriter contest was also held this season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] From ten of the most popular submissions, each of the final two contestants chose a song to perform, although neither of their selections was used as the "coronation song".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The winning song, "The Time of My Life", was recorded by David Cook and released on May 22, 2008.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The eighth season premiered on January 13, 2009.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] This season featured the first major change to the judging panel; a fourth judge, Kara DioGuardi, was introduced.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Mike Darnell, the president of alternative programming for Fox, stated that the season would focus more on the contestants' personal life.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] This was also the first season without executive producer Nigel Lythgoe who left to focus on the international versions of his show *So You Think You Can Dance*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The Hollywood round was moved to the Kodak Theatre for 2009 and was also extended to two weeks.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] *Idol Gives Back* was canceled for this season due to the global recession at the time.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] There were 13 finalists this season, but two were eliminated in the first result show of the finals.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] A new feature introduced was the "Judges' Save", and Matt Giraud was saved from elimination at the top seven by the judges when he received the fewest votes.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The next week, Lil Rounds and Anoop Desai were eliminated.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The two finalists were Kris Allen and Adam Lambert, both of whom had previously landed in the bottom three at the top five.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Allen won the contest in the most controversial voting result since the second season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] It was claimed, and then later retracted, that 38 million of the 100 million votes cast on the night came from Allen's home state of Arkansas alone, and that AT&T employees unfairly influenced the votes by giving lessons on power-texting at viewing parties in Arkansas.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Both Allen and Lambert released the coronation song, "No Boundaries" which was co-written by DioGuardi.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] This is the first season in which the winner failed to achieve gold album status.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The ninth season premiered on January 12, 2010.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Ryan Seacrest returned as host, and Randy Jackson, Kara DioGuardi, and Simon Cowell returned as judges.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Paula Abdul left the show and Ellen DeGeneres replaced Abdul at the start of Hollywood Week.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] One of the most prominent auditioners this season was General Larry Platt whose performance of "Pants on the Ground" became a viral hit song.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Crystal Bowersox, who has Type-I diabetes, fell ill due to diabetic ketoacidosis on the morning of the girls performance night for the top 20 week and was hospitalized.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The schedule was rearranged so the boys performed first and she could perform the following night instead; she later revealed that Ken Warwick, the show producer, wanted to disqualify her but she begged to be allowed to stay on the show.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Michael Lynche was the lowest vote getter at top nine and was given the Judges' Save.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The next week Katie Stevens and Andrew Garcia were eliminated.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] That week, Adam Lambert was invited back to be a mentor, the first *Idol* alum to do so.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] *Idol Gives Back* returned this season on April 21, 2010, and raised $45 million.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] A special tribute to Simon Cowell was presented in the finale for his final season with the show.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Many figures from the show's past, including Paula Abdul, made an appearance.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The final two contestants were Lee DeWyze and Bowersox.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] DeWyze was declared the winner during the May 26 finale.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] No new song was used as coronation song this year; instead, the two finalists each released a cover song – DeWyze chose U2's "Beautiful Day", and Bowersox chose Patty Griffin's "Up to the Mountain".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] This is the first season where neither finalist achieved significant album sales.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The tenth season premiered on January 19, 2011.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Ryan Seacrest returned as host and Randy Jackson returned as a judge.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Many changes were introduced this season, from the format to the personnel of the show.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Jennifer Lopez and Steven Tyler joined Randy Jackson as judges following the departures of Simon Cowell (who left to launch the American version of *The X Factor*), Kara DioGuardi (whose contract was not renewed) and Ellen DeGeneres, who left the show on her own accord.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Randy Jackson was the only judge from the ninth season to return for the tenth.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Nigel Lythgoe returned as executive producer.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Jimmy Iovine, chairman of the Interscope Geffen A&M label group, the new partner of *American Idol*, acted as the in-house mentor in place of weekly guest mentors, although in later episodes special guest mentors such as Beyoncé, will.i.am and Lady Gaga were brought in.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The tenth season is the first to include online auditions where contestants could submit a 40-second video audition via Myspace.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Karen Rodriguez was one such auditioner and reached the final rounds.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] One of the more prominent contestants this year was Chris Medina, whose story of caring for his brain-damaged fiancée received widespread coverage.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Casey Abrams, who suffers from ulcerative colitis, was hospitalized twice and missed the Top 13 result show.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The judges used their one save on Abrams on the Top 11, and as a result this was the first season that 11 finalists went on tour instead of 10.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] In the following week, Naima Adedapo and Thia Megia were both eliminated.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Pia Toscano, one of the presumed favorites to advance far in the season, was unexpectedly eliminated on April 7, 2011, finishing in ninth place.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Her elimination drew criticisms from some former *Idol* contestants, as well as actor Tom Hanks.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] After *Idol*, Jennifer Lopez helped guide her career.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The two finalists in 2011 were Lauren Alaina and Scotty McCreery, both teenage country singers.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] McCreery won the competition on May 25, being the youngest male winner and the fourth male in a row to win *American Idol*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] McCreery released his first single, "I Love You This Big", as his coronation song, and Alaina released "Like My Mother Does".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] McCreery's debut album, *Clear as Day*, became the first debut album by an *Idol* winner to reach No.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] 1 on the US *Billboard* 200 since Ruben Studdard's *Soulful* in 2003, and he became the youngest male artist to reach No.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The eleventh season premiered on January 18, 2012.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Ryan Seacrest returned as host and Steven Tyler, Jennifer Lopez, and Randy Jackson returned as judges.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] One more finalist would join the Top 24 making it the Top 25, which was later revealed to be Jermaine Jones.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] However, on March 14, Jones was disqualified in 12th place for concealing arrests and outstanding warrants.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Jones denied the accusation that he concealed his arrests.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Finalist Phillip Phillips suffered from kidney pain and was taken to the hospital before the Top 13 results show, and later received medical procedure to alleviate a blockage caused by kidney stones.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] He was reported to have eight surgeries during his Idol run, and had considered quitting the show due to the pain.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] He underwent surgery to remove the stones and reconstruct his kidney soon after the season had finished.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Jessica Sanchez received the fewest votes during the Top 7 week, and the judges decided to use their "save" option on her, making her the first female recipient of the save.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The following week, unlike previous seasons, Colton Dixon was the only contestant sent home.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Sanchez later made the final two, the first season where a recipient of the save reached the finale.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Phillips became the winner, beating Sanchez.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] During the finale, fifth season finalist Ace Young proposed marriage to third season runner-up Diana DeGarmo on stage – which she accepted.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Phillips released "Home" as his coronation song, while Sanchez released "Change Nothing".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Phillips' "Home" has since become the best selling of all coronation songs, with over 5 million copies sold.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The twelfth season premiered on January 16, 2013.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Judges Jennifer Lopez and Steven Tyler left the show after two seasons.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Randy Jackson was the only judge from the eleventh season to return for the twelfth.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] This season's judging panel consisted of Randy Jackson, along with Mariah Carey, Keith Urban and Nicki Minaj.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] This was the first season since the ninth season to have four judges on the panel.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The pre-season buzz and the early episodes of the show were dominated by the feud between the judges Minaj and Carey after a video of their dispute was leaked to TMZ.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The top 10 contestants started with five males and five females, however, the males were eliminated consecutively in the first five weeks, with Lazaro Arbos the last male to be eliminated.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] For the first time in the show's history, the top 5 contestants were all female.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] It was also the first time that the judges' "save" was not used, the top four contestants were therefore given an extra week to perform again with their votes carried over with no elimination in the first week.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] 23-year-old Candice Glover won the season with Kree Harrison taking the runner-up spot.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Glover became the first female to win *American Idol* since Jordin Sparks, who won the show in 2007.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Glover released "I Am Beautiful" as a single while Harrison released "All Cried Out" immediately after the show.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Glover sold poorly with her debut album, and this is also the first season that the runner-up was not signed by a music label.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Towards the end of the season, Randy Jackson, the last remaining of the original judges, announced he would no longer serve as a judge to pursue other business ventures.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Both judges Mariah Carey and Nicki Minaj also decided to leave after one season to focus on their music careers.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The thirteenth season premiered on January 15, 2014.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Ryan Seacrest returned as host and Keith Urban returned as a judge.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Randy Jackson returned, though Jackson moved from the judging panel to the role of in-mentor.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Mariah Carey and Nicki Minaj left the panel after one season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Former judge Jennifer Lopez and former mentor Harry Connick, Jr. joined Urban on the panel.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Connick Jr. served as a mentor for *Idol* in 2010 and 2012.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Also, Nigel Lythgoe and Ken Warwick were replaced as executive producers by Per Blankens, Jesse Ignjatovic and Evan Pragger.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Bill DeRonde replaced Warwick as a director of the audition episodes, while Louis J.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Horvitz replaced Gregg Gelfand as a director of the show.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] This was the first season where the contestants were permitted to perform in the final rounds songs they wrote themselves.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] In the Top 8, Sam Woolf received the fewest votes, but he was saved from elimination by the judges.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The 500th episode of the series was the Top 3 performance night.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Caleb Johnson was named the winner of the season, with Jena Irene as the runner-up.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Johnson released "As Long as You Love Me" as his coronation single while Irene released "We Are One".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The fourteenth season premiered on January 7, 2015.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Ryan Seacrest returned as host, and Jennifer Lopez, Keith Urban and Harry Connick, Jr. returned for their respective fourth, third and second seasons as judges.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Eighth season runner-up Adam Lambert filled in for Urban during the New York City auditions.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Randy Jackson did not return as the in-house mentor and left the show permanently.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Scott Borchetta replaced Jackson as the mentor.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Changes this season include only airing one episode a week during the final ten.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Coca-Cola ended their longtime sponsorship of the show and Ford Motor Company maintained a reduced role.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The winner of the season also received a recording contract with Big Machine Records.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Nick Fradiani won the season, defeating Clark Beckham.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Fradiani became the first winner from the Northeast region.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Fradiani released "Beautiful Life" as his coronation single while Beckham released "Champion".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Jax, the third place finalist, also released a single called "Forcefield".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Fox announced on May 11, 2015, that the fifteenth season would be the final season of *American Idol*; as such, the season was expected to have an additional focus on the program's alumni.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Ryan Seacrest returned as host, with Harry Connick Jr., Keith Urban, and Jennifer Lopez all returning as judges.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The fifteenth season premiered on January 6, 2016.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The season was shortened by four weeks compared to previous years.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] During the finale episode, President Barack Obama praised the millions of young people that voted for contestants and pitched that they vote in the upcoming election.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The farewell season concluded on April 7, 2016.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Trent Harmon won the season against runner-up La'Porsha Renae.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Harmon released "Falling" co-written by Keith Urban as his coronation song.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Renae's "Battles", third-place finisher Dalton Rapattoni's "Strike A Match" and fourth-place finisher MacKenzie Bourg's "Roses" were also released as singles.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] In early 2017, *Variety* reported that Fremantle Media was in talks to revive the show for NBC or for its original network, Fox.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] A dispute between Fremantle and Core Media Group derailed these plans.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] In May 2017, ABC was making a bid to revive the program.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] ABC acquired the rights to the series, and *American Idol* returned for the 2017–18 television season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] In July 2017, it was announced that Ryan Seacrest would return as host, and by September 2017 it was revealed that Katy Perry, Luke Bryan and Lionel Richie would serve as judges.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The sixteenth season premiered on March 11, 2018.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] This was the first season of *American Idol* to air on ABC.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The season was again shortened compared to the previous season to twelve weeks, with multiple elimination in the final rounds.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Unlike previous seasons where only two finalists remained in the final episode, three finalists performed in the finale.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 21, 2018, the season concluded with Maddie Poppe crowned the winner, beating Caleb Lee Hutchinson as runner-up and Gabby Barrett in third place.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Her winning song was "Going, Going, Gone".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Caleb Lee Hutchinson released "Johnny Cash Heart" as a single, while Gabby Barrett's song was "Rivers Deep".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] ABC renewed the revival series for another season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Seacrest returned as host, and Bryan, Perry and Richie returned as judges.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The seventeenth season premiered on March 3, 2019.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] For the finale, the show no longer features separate performance and result shows.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 19, 2019, the season concluded with three finalists, with Madison VanDenburg eliminated in third place after performing two songs, and the final two performing their last song.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] For the first time, there were no separate performance and grand finale shows this season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Laine Hardy was crowned the winner and Alejandro Aranda runner-up.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Hardy released a single, "Flame", immediately after the win, but Aranda did not.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] However, Aranda later released a song he performed in the finale, "Tonight", under the name Scarypoolparty on June 28, 2019.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 13, 2019, the series was renewed for an eighteenth season and it premiered on February 16, 2020.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] For the first time, due to the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic, from the top 20 to the finale, the contestants performed in their own homes, while Ryan Seacrest hosted the show remotely in his own home in Los Angeles with the judges also in their respective homes.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The season was also further truncated, with the top 5 performing in the finale.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Each finalist also performed only two songs for the finale.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 17, the season concluded, with Just Sam crowned as the winner, with Arthur Gunn finishing as the runner-up.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] "Rise Up", the song Just Sam performed for their audition and reprised on the finale, was released as their debut song.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 15, 2020, ABC renewed the series for a nineteenth season and it premiered on February 14, 2021.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Later in October, it was announced that Bobby Bones would return as mentor.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 23, the season concluded, with Chayce Beckham crowned the winner, with Willie Spence finishing as the runner-up and Grace Kinstler in third place.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] "23", the song Chayce Beckham wrote and performed for Top 4, was released as his debut song.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 13, 2021, ABC renewed the series for a twentieth season and it premiered on February 27, 2022.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On December 31, it was announced that Bones would not be returning as a mentor.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 22, the season concluded, with Noah Thompson crowned as the winner, with HunterGirl finishing as the runner-up and Leah Marlene in third place.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] "One Day Tonight", the song Noah Thompson performed for the Grand Finale, was released as his debut song.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 13, 2022, ABC renewed the series for a twenty-first season and it premiered on February 19, 2023.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 21, the season concluded, with Iam Tongi crowned as the winner, with Megan Danielle finishing as the runner-up and Colin Stough placing third.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 16, 2023, ABC renewed the series for a twenty-second season and it premiered on February 18, 2024.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] In February 2024, Perry announced that the season would be her last.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 19, the season concluded, with Abi Carter crowned as the winner, with Will Moseley finishing as the runner-up and Jack Blocker placing third.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 10, 2024, ABC renewed the series for a twenty-third season; it was also announced the network was in-talks with "high-profile stars" to replace the outgoing Perry.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On July 31, 2024, it was announced Seacrest would return as host, with Bryan and Richie returning as judges; Underwood was named as Perry's successor.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 18, the season concluded, with Jamal Roberts crowned as the winner, with John Foster finishing as the runner-up and Breanna Nix placing third.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 9, 2025, it was announced the series had been renewed for a twenty-fourth season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] Three months later, it was announced the season would premiere in January 2026, with Bryan, Richie, and Underwood returning as judges; Seacrest returned as host.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] The twenty-fourth season premiered on January 26, 2026.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p02] On May 11, the season concluded, with Hannah Harper crowned as the winner, with Jordan McCullough finishing as the runner-up and Keyla Richardson placing third.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Seasonal rankings (based on average total viewers per episode) of *American Idol*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The growth continued into the next season, starting with a season premiere of 26.5 million.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The season attracted an average of 21.7 million viewers, and was placed second overall amongst the 18–49 age group.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The finale night when Ruben Studdard won over Clay Aiken was also the highest-rated ever *American Idol* episode at 38.1 million for the final hour.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] By the third season, the show had become the top show in the 18–49 demographic a position it has held for all subsequent years up to and including the tenth season, and its competition stages ranked first in the nationwide overall ratings.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] By the fourth season, *American Idol* had become the most-watched series amongst all viewers on American TV for the first time, with an average viewership of 26.8 million.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The show reached its peak in the fifth season with numbers averaging 30.6 million per episode, and this season remains the highest-rated of the series.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The show was dubbed "the Death Star", and competing networks often rearranged their schedules in order to minimize losses.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] However, the sixth season also showed a steady decline in viewership over the course of the season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The season finale saw a drop in ratings of 16% from the previous year.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The sixth season was the first season wherein the average results show rated higher than the competition stages (unlike in the previous seasons), and became the second-highest-rated of the series after the preceding season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The loss of viewers continued into the seventh season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The premiere was down 11% among total viewers, and the results show in which Kristy Lee Cook was eliminated delivered its lowest-rated Wednesday show among the 18–34 demo since the first season in 2002.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] However, the ratings rebounded for the seventh-season finale with the excitement over the battle of the Davids, and improved over the sixth season as the series' third most watched finale.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The strong finish of season seven also helped Fox become the most watched TV network in the country for the first time since its inception, a first ever in American television history for a non-Big Three major broadcast network.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Overall ratings for the season were down 10% from the sixth season, which is in line with the fall in viewership across all networks due in part to the 2007–2008 Writers Guild of America strike.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The declining trend however continued into the eighth season, as total viewers numbers fell by 5–10% for early episodes compared to the seventh season, and by 9% for the finale.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In the ninth season, *Idol*'s six-year extended streak of perfection in the ratings was broken, when NBC's coverage of the 2010 Winter Olympics on February 17 beat *Idol* in the same time slot with 30.1 million viewers over *Idol'*s 18.4 million.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Nevertheless, *American Idol* overall finished its ninth season as the most watched TV series for the sixth year running, breaking the previous record of five consecutive seasons achieved by CBS' *All in the Family* and NBC's *The Cosby Show*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In the tenth season, the total viewer numbers for the first week of shows fell 12–13%, and by up to 23% in the 18–49 demo compared to the ninth season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Later episodes, however, retained viewers better, and the season ended on a high with a significant increase in viewership for the finale – up 12% for the adults 18–49 demographic and a 21% increase in total viewers from the ninth-season finale.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] While the overall viewer number has increased this season, its viewer demographics have continued to age year on year – the median age this season was 47.2 compared to a median age of 32.1 in its first season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The demographics also became "whiter" over time and less diverse.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Nevertheless, in the 2010–11 television season, Fox maintained its lead on over other networks with its seventh consecutive season of victory overall in the 18–49 demographic ratings in the United States.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The eleventh season, however, suffered a steep drop in ratings, a drop attributed by some to the arrival of new shows such as *The Voice* and *The X Factor*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The ratings for the first two episodes of the eleventh season fell 16–21% in overall viewer numbers and 24–27% in the 18/49 demo, while the season finale fell 27% in total viewer number and 30% in the 18–49 demo.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The average viewership for the season fell below 20 million viewers the first time since 2003, a drop of 23% in total viewers and 30% in the 18/49 demo.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The loss of viewers continued into the twelfth season, which saw the show hitting a number of series low in the 18–49 demo.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The finale had 7.2 million fewer viewers than the previous season, and saw a drop of 44% in the 18–49 demo.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The season viewers averaged at 13.3 million, a drop of 24% from the previous season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] On May 11, 2015, prior to the fourteenth-season finale, Fox announced that the fifteenth season of *American Idol* would be its last.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Despite these changes, the show's ratings would decline more sharply.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The fourteenth-season finale was the lowest-rated finale ever, with an average of only 8.03 million viewers watching the finale.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The show's ratings, however, rebounded in its final season and ended its run in 2016 as Fox's first-ever program to conclude its run without dropping from the Nielsen Top 30 most-watched television shows in each of its seasons.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] For the revived series on ABC, the ratings were lower but remained stable compared to previous seasons on Fox.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The finale of the seventeenth season was slightly more watched than the sixteenth.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Early reviews were mixed in their assessment.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Ken Tucker of *Entertainment Weekly* considered that "As TV, *American Idol* is crazily entertaining; as music, it's dust-mote inconsequential".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Others, however, thought that "the most striking aspect of the series was the genuine talent it revealed".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] It was also described as a "sadistic musical bake-off", and "a romp in humiliation".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Other aspects of the show have attracted criticisms.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The decision to send the first season winner to sing the national anthem at the Lincoln Memorial on the first anniversary of the September 11 attacks in 2002 was also poorly received by many.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Some in the entertainment industry were critical of the star-making aspect of the show.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Usher, a mentor on the show, bemoaning the loss of the "true art form of music", thought that shows like *American Idol* made it seem "so easy that everyone can do it, and that it can happen overnight", and that "television is a lie".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Musician Michael Feinstein, while acknowledging that the show had uncovered promising performers, said that *American Idol* "isn't really about music.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] LeAnn Rimes, commenting on Carrie Underwood winning Best Female Artist in Country Music Awards over Faith Hill in 2006, said that "Carrie has not paid her dues long enough to fully deserve that award".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] It is a common theme that has been echoed by many others.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Elton John, who had appeared as a mentor in the show but turned down an offer to be a judge on *American Idol*, commenting on talent shows in general, said that "there have been some good acts but the only way to sustain a career is to pay your dues in small clubs".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] *American Idol* revolutionized American pop culture and the pop idol process and has provided an opportunity for many to bypass the small club scene and allow a much larger audience to participate in and select the next potential chart topping performer.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The success of the show's alumni, however, has led to a more positive assessment of the show, and the show was described as having "proven it has a valid way to pick talent and a proven way to sell records".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] While the industry is divided on the show success, its impact is felt particularly strongly in the country music format.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] According to a CMT exec, reflecting on the success of Idol alumni in the country genre, "if you want to try and get famous fast by going to a cattle call audition on TV, Idol reasonably remains the first choice for anyone", and that country music and Idol "go together well".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] 48 on its list of the 60 Best Series of All Time.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Throughout the series, twelve of the seventeen *Idol* winners, including its first five, had come from the Southern United States.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] A large number of other finalists during the series' run have also hailed from the American South, including Clay Aiken, Kellie Pickler, and Chris Daughtry, who are all from North Carolina.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In 2012, an analysis of the 131 contestants who have appeared in the finals of all seasons of the show up to that point found that 48% have some connection to the Southern United States.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The show itself was popular in the Southern United States, with households in the Southeastern United States 10% more likely to watch *American Idol* during the eighth season in 2009, and those in the East Central region, such as Kentucky, were 16 percent more likely to tune into the series.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Data from Nielsen SoundScan, a music-sales tracking service, showed that of the 47 million CDs sold by *Idol* contestants through January 2010, 85 percent were by contestants with ties to the American South.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Others also suggest that the Southern character of these contestants appeal to the South, as well as local pride.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] According to fifth season winner Taylor Hicks, who is from the state of Alabama, "People in the South have a lot of pride ...
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] For five consecutive seasons, starting in the seventh season, the title was given to a white male who plays the guitar – a trend that *Idol* pundits call the "White guy with guitar" or "WGWG" factor.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Some fans call the final performance of the night the "pimp spot" because it usually receives a big boost in votes, due to the recency effect.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] By performing first, a performer may benefit from the primacy effect, but any other early performance may be stifled.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The second performance spot is sometimes called the "un-pimp spot" because it is the least beneficial.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The show was criticized in earlier seasons over the onerous contract contestants had to sign that gave excessive control to 19 Entertainment over their future careers and handed a large part of their future earnings to the management.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Individual contestants have generated controversy in this competition for their past actions or for being 'ringers' planted by the producers.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] A number of contestants have been disqualified for various reasons, such as for having an existing contract or undisclosed criminal record, although the show has also been accused of a double standard for disqualifying some but not others.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Voting results have been a consistent source of controversy.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The mechanism of voting has aroused considerable criticism, most notably in the second season when Ruben Studdard beat Clay Aiken in a close vote, and in the eighth season, when the massive increase in text votes fueled the texting controversy.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Concerns about power voting have been expressed from the first season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Since 2004, votes also have been affected to a limited degree by online communities such as DialIdol and Vote for the Worst.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The enormous success of the show and the revenue it generated were transformative for the Fox Broadcasting Company.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] On several occasions, notably in 2003 and 2008, *American Idol* overtook the Academy Awards as the most-watched non-sports entertainment event on U.S. television, marking the most recent time as of 2026 that a live regular non-sports primetime series has garnered such viewership in the country.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The show pushed Fox to become the number one U.S.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] TV network in overall viewers in 2008 and among adults aged 18–49, the key demographic coveted by advertisers, for an unprecedented eight consecutive years from 2005 to 2012.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The show, its creator Simon Fuller claimed, "saved Fox".
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The show's massive success in the mid-2000s to early 2010s spawned a number of imitating singing-competition shows, such as *Rock Star*, *Nashville Star*, *The Voice*, *Rising Star*, *The Sing-Off*, and *The X Factor*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The number of imitative singing shows on American television had reached 17 by 2016.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Its format also served as a blueprint for non-singing TV shows such as *Dancing with the Stars* and *So You Think You Can Dance*, most of which contribute to the current highly competitive reality TV landscape on American television.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] As one of the most successful shows in U.S. television history, *American Idol* has had a strong impact not just on television, but also in the wider world of entertainment.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] It helped create a number of highly successful recording artists, such as Kelly Clarkson, Daughtry and Carrie Underwood, as well as others of varying notability.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The alumni of the show's original run scored 13 Grammy Award wins out of 54 Grammy nominations up to its end in 2016, with Underwood and Clarkson receiving 10 wins combined.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Various *American Idol* alumni had success on various record charts around the world; in the U.S. they had achieved 345 number ones on the *Billboard* charts in its first 10 years, and 458 by its last year of broadcast in 2016, with 100 achieved by Kelly Clarkson alone.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] According to Fred Bronson, author of books on the Billboard charts, no other entity has ever created as many hit-making artists and bestselling albums and singles.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In 2007, *American Idol* alums accounted for 2.1% of all music sales.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Its alumni have a massive impact on radio; in 2007, *American Idol* had become "a dominant force in radio" according to Rich Meyer, president of the radio station monitoring research company Mediabase.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] By 2010, four winners each had more than a million radio spins, with Kelly Clarkson leading the field with over four million spins.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] At the end of the show's original run on Fox in 2016, *Idol'*s contestants have sold more than 60 million albums in the U.S. and more than 100 million records globally, more than 175 of which are certified platinum or gold.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Its participants have generated more than 450 Billboard No.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] 1 hits and sold more than 260 million digital downloads.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The impact of *American Idol* was also strongly felt in musical theater, where many of *Idol* alumni have forged successful careers.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The striking effect of former *American Idol* contestants on Broadway has been noted and commented on.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The casting of a popular *Idol* contestant can lead to significantly increased ticket sales.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Other alumni have gone on to work in television and films, the most notable being Jennifer Hudson who, on the recommendation of the *Idol* vocal coach Debra Byrd, won a role in *Dreamgirls* and eventually went on to win an Academy Award for her performance.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] She later became the show's first and only alumnus ever to win the EGOT (Emmy, Grammy, Oscar, and Tony).
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In 2007, a musical based on the show, *Idol: The Musical*, played off-Broadway.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The musical closed after its official opening night.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The dominance of *American Idol* in the ratings had made it the most profitable show in U.S.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The show was estimated to generate $900 million for the year 2004 through sales of TV ads, albums, merchandise and concert tickets.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] By the seventh season, the show was estimated to earn around $900 million from its ad revenue alone, not including ancillary sponsorship deals and other income.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] One estimate puts the total TV revenue for the first eight seasons of *American Idol* at $6.4 billion.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Sponsors that bought fully integrated packages can expect a variety of promotions of their products on the show, such as product placement, adverts and product promotion integrated into the show, and various promotional opportunities.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Other off-air promotional partners pay for the rights to feature "Idol" branding on their packaging, products and marketing programs.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] *American Idol* also partnered with Disney in its theme park attraction The American Idol Experience.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Ford Motor Company and Coca-Cola were two of the first sponsors of *American Idol* in its first season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The sponsorship deal cost around $10 million in the first season, rising to $35 million by the seventh season, and between $50 and $60 million in the tenth season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The third major sponsor AT&T Wireless joined in the second season but ended after the twelfth season, and Coca-Cola officially ended its sponsorship after the thirteenth season amidst the declining ratings of *Idol* in the mid-2010s. iTunes sponsored the show since the seventh season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Coca-Cola's archrival PepsiCo declined to sponsor *American Idol* at the show's start.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] What the *Los Angeles Times* later called "missing one of the biggest marketing opportunities in a generation" contributed to Pepsi losing market share, by 2010 falling to third place from second in the United States.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] PepsiCo sponsored the American version of Cowell's *The X Factor* in hopes of not repeating its *Idol* mistake until its cancellation.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] For the revived series on ABC, Macy's and Johnson & Johnson's Zyrtec signed on as the major sponsors of the show.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The top ten (eleven in the tenth season, five in the fourteenth season, and seven in the sixteenth season) toured at the end of every season except for the fifteenth and seventeenth seasons.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In the twelfth season tour a semi-finalist who won a sing-off was also added to the tour.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Kellogg's Pop-Tarts was the sponsor for the first seven seasons, and Guitar Hero was added for the seventh season tour.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] M&M's Pretzel Chocolate Candies was a sponsor of the ninth season tour.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The fifth season tour was the most successful tour with gross of over $35 million.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] However no concert tour was organized in the fifteenth and seventeenth seasons, the only seasons not to have an associated tour.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The sixteenth season tour featured the band In Real Life as an opener on select dates.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] 19 Recordings, a recording label owned by 19 Entertainment, currently hold the rights to phonographic material recorded by all the contestants.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] 19 Recordings originally partnered with Bertelsmann Music Group (BMG) to promote and distribute the recordings through its labels RCA Records, Arista Records, J Records, and Jive Records.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] From 2005–2007, BMG partnered with Sony Music Entertainment to form a joint venture known as Sony BMG Music Entertainment.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] From 2008 to 2010, following their acquisition of BMG, Sony Music handled the distribution of *American Idol'*s music.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In 2010, UMG's Interscope-Geffen-A&M Records replaced Sony as the music label for *American Idol*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] On February 14, 2009, The Walt Disney Company debuted "The American Idol Experience" at its Disney's Hollywood Studios theme park at the Walt Disney World Resort in Florida.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In this live production, co-produced by 19 Entertainment, park guests chose from a list of songs and auditioned privately for Disney cast members.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Those selected then performed on a stage in a 1000-seat theater replicating the *Idol* set.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Three judges, whose mannerisms and style mimicked those of the real *Idol* judges, critiqued the performances.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Audience members then voted for their favorite performer.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] There were several preliminary-round shows during the day that culminated in a "finals" show in the evening where one of the winners of the previous rounds that day was selected as the overall winner.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The winner of the finals show received a "Dream Ticket" that granted them front-of-the-line privileges at any future *American Idol* audition.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The attraction closed on August 30, 2014.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In Latin America, the show is broadcast and subtitled by Sony Entertainment Television.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In Southeast Asia, it is broadcast by Sony Channel every Monday and Tuesday nine or ten hours after since its revival.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In Philippines, it is aired every Thursday and Friday nine or ten hours after its United States telecast; from 2004 to 2007 on ABC; 2008–11 on QTV, then GMA News TV; 2012–16, 2018–19 on ETC; and since 2024 on TV5.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In Indonesia, it was aired on RCTI in the 2002 to 2003 season with the Indonesian subtitles, before Indonesian Idol was held in the 2004, aired after each episode ended, and in the 2011 to 2013 season it was broadcast by B-Channel (now RTV).
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In Australia, it aired a few hours after the U.S. telecast.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] It was aired on Network Ten from 2002 to 2008 and then again in 2013.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Between 2008 and 2012 it aired on Fox8 and the thirteenth and fourteenth seasons (2014–15) it aired on digital channel, Eleven, a sister channel to Network Ten.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] Its final season (2016) aired on Fox8 hours after the original U.S. broadcast.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] The show enjoyed a lot of popularity in Australia throughout the 2000s before declining in the ratings.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In the United Kingdom, episodes were aired one day after the U.S. broadcast on digital channel ITV2.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In the twelfth season, the episodes aired on 5*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] It was also aired in Ireland on TV3 two days after the telecast.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In Brazil and Israel, the show airs two days after its original broadcast, and broadcast live during the season finale.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In the instances where the airing is delayed, the shows may sometimes be combined into one episode to summarize the results.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In Italy, the twelfth season was broadcast by La3.
[src:baseball-prospectus/american-idol-p03] In Singapore, The show was broadcast on Mediacorp Channel 5 for the ninth and tenth seasons.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-awards-p01] ¹ A combined award is given for the American and National Leagues.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-digest] The magazine was created in 1942 by Herbert F.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-digest] Simons, a sportswriter for the *Chicago Daily Times*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-digest] Simons first published the magazine in August 1942, and served as its editor-in-chief until 1963.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-digest] In 1981, Joan Whaley was published as its first female contributor.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-digest] After publishing on a 9 or 12 issue per year schedule, in 2009 the magazine was scaled back to six issues.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-digest] In March 2012, *Baseball Digest* merged with the professional scouting service ProScouts LLC.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-digest] This relaunch included major changes to the magazine's format, as it was published in full color for the first time and was made available in more locations.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-digest] In May 2018, Rick Cerrone, former Public Relations Director with the New York Yankees (and not to be confused with the Yankees catcher of a similar name), became the fourth editor in the magazine's history.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-digest] Cerrone was tasked with re-imagining the publication.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-digest] Starting with the January/February 2019 issue, the magazine changed to a heavier paper stock and increased the number of pages.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-digest] On July 4, 2019, Grandstand Publishing, LLC, announced the introduction of BaseballDigestArchive.com, a web-based subscription service featuring every issue of Baseball Digest.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-digest] In May 2021, ProScouts LLC, headed by entrepreneur David Fagley, purchased the remaining outstanding shares held by long-time publisher Norman Jacobs, who remains as Publisher Emeritus.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The initial objective of the batting team is to have a player reach first base safely; this occurs either when the batter hits the ball and reaches first base before an opponent retrieves the ball and touches the base, or when the pitcher persists in throwing the ball out of the batter's reach.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Players on the batting team who reach first base without being called "out" can attempt to advance to subsequent bases as a runner, either immediately or during teammates' turns batting.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The fielding team tries to prevent runs by using the ball to get batters or runners "out", which forces them out of the field of play.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The pitcher can get the batter out by throwing three pitches which result in strikes, while fielders can get the batter out by catching a batted ball before it touches the ground, and can get a runner out by tagging them with the ball while the runner is not touching a base.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The opposing teams switch back and forth between batting and fielding; the batting team's turn to bat is over once the fielding team records three outs.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] One turn batting for each team constitutes an inning.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A game is usually composed of nine innings, and the team with the greater number of runs at the end of the game wins.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Most games end after the ninth inning, but if scores are tied at that point, extra innings are usually played.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Baseball has no game clock, though some competitions feature pace-of-play regulations such as a pitch clock to shorten game time.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Baseball evolved from older bat-and-ball games already being played in England by the mid-18th century.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] This game was brought by immigrants to North America, where the modern version developed.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In addition to North America, baseball spread throughout the rest of the Americas and the Asia–Pacific in the 19th and 20th centuries, and is now considered the most popular sport in parts of Central and South America, the Caribbean, and East Asia, particularly in Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In Major League Baseball (MLB), the highest level of professional baseball in the United States and Canada, teams are divided into the National League (NL) and American League (AL), each with three divisions: East, West, and Central.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The MLB champion is determined by playoffs that culminate in the World Series.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The top level of play is similarly split in Japan between the Central and Pacific Leagues and in Cuba between the West League and East League.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The World Baseball Classic, organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation, is the major international competition of the sport and attracts the top national teams from around the world.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Baseball was played at the Olympic Games from 1992 to 2008, and was reinstated on a one-off basis in 2020.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A baseball game is played between two teams, each composed of nine players, that take turns playing offense (batting and baserunning) and defense (pitching and fielding).
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A pair of turns, one at bat and one in the field, by each team constitutes an inning.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A game consists of nine innings (seven innings at the high school level and in doubleheaders in college and Minor League Baseball; and six innings at the Little League level).
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] One team—customarily the visiting team—bats in the top, or first half, of every inning.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The other team—customarily the home team—bats in the bottom, or second half, of every inning.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The goal of the game is to score more points (runs) than the other team.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The players on the team at bat attempt to score runs by touching all four bases, in order, set at the corners of the square-shaped baseball diamond.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A player bats at home plate and must attempt to safely reach a base before proceeding, counterclockwise, from first base, to second base, third base, and back home to score a run.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The team in the field attempts to prevent runs from scoring by recording outs, which remove opposing players from offensive action until their next turn at bat comes up again.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] When three outs are recorded, the teams switch roles for the next half-inning.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] If the score of the game is tied after nine innings, extra innings are played to resolve the contest.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Many amateur games, particularly unorganized ones, involve different numbers of players and innings.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The game is played on a field whose primary boundaries, the foul lines, extend forward from home plate at 45-degree angles.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The 90-degree area within the foul lines is referred to as fair territory; the 270-degree area outside them is foul territory.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The part of the field enclosed by the bases and several yards beyond them is the infield; the area farther beyond the infield is the outfield.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In the middle of the infield is a raised pitcher's mound, with a rectangular rubber plate (the rubber) at its center.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The outer boundary of the outfield is typically demarcated by a raised fence, which may be of any material and height.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The fair territory between home plate and the outfield boundary is baseball's field of play, though significant events can take place in foul territory, as well.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Protective helmets are also standard equipment for all batters.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] At the beginning of each half-inning, the nine players of the fielding team arrange themselves around the field.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] One of them, the pitcher, stands on the pitcher's mound.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The pitcher begins the pitching delivery with one foot on the rubber, pushing off it to gain velocity when throwing toward home plate.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Another fielding team player, the catcher, squats on the far side of home plate, facing the pitcher.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The rest of the fielding team faces home plate, typically arranged as four infielders—who set up along or within a few yards outside the imaginary lines (basepaths) between first, second, and third base—and three outfielders.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In the standard arrangement, there is a first baseman positioned several steps to the left of first base, a second baseman to the right of second base, a shortstop to the left of second base, and a third baseman to the right of third base.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The basic outfield positions are left fielder, center fielder, and right fielder.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] With the exception of the catcher, all fielders are required to be in fair territory when the pitch is delivered.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A neutral umpire sets up behind the catcher.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Other umpires will be distributed around the field as well.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Play starts with a member of the batting team, the batter, standing in either of the two batter's boxes next to home plate, holding a bat.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The batter waits for the pitcher to throw a pitch (the ball) toward home plate, and attempts to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The catcher catches pitches that the batter does not hit—as a result of either electing not to swing or failing to connect—and returns them to the pitcher.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A batter who hits the ball into the field of play must drop the bat and begin running toward first base, at which point the player is referred to as a *runner* (or, until the play is over, a *batter-runner*).
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A batter-runner who reaches first base without being put out is said to be *safe* and is on base.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A batter-runner may choose to remain at first base or attempt to advance to second base or even beyond—however far the player believes can be reached safely.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base despite proper play by the fielders has recorded a hit.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A player who reaches first base safely on a hit is credited with a single.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] If a player makes it to second base safely as a direct result of a hit, it is a double; third base, a triple.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air within the foul lines over the entire outfield (and outfield fence, if there is one), or if the batter-runner otherwise safely circles all the bases, it is a home run: the batter and any runners on base may all freely circle the bases, each scoring a run.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] This is the most desirable result for the batter.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The ultimate and most desirable result possible for a batter would be to hit a home run while all three bases are occupied or "loaded", thus scoring four runs on a single hit.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base due to a fielding mistake is not credited with a hit—instead, the responsible fielder is charged with an error.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Any runners already on base may attempt to advance on batted balls that land, or contact the ground, in fair territory, before or after the ball lands.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A runner on first base *must* attempt to advance if a ball lands in play, as only one runner may occupy a base at any given time; the same applies for other runners if they are on a base that a teammate is forced to advance to.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] If a ball hit into play rolls foul before passing through the infield, it becomes dead and any runners must return to the base they occupied when the play began.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air and caught before it lands, the batter has flied out and any runners on base may attempt to advance only if they tag up (contact the base they occupied when the play began, as or after the ball is caught).
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Runners may also attempt to advance to the next base while the pitcher is in the process of delivering the ball to home plate; a successful effort is a stolen base.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A pitch that is not hit into the field of play is called either a strike or a ball.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A batter against whom three strikes are recorded strikes out.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A batter against whom four balls are recorded is awarded a base on balls or walk, a free advance to first base.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] While the team at bat is trying to score runs, the team in the field is attempting to record outs.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In addition to the strikeout and flyout, common ways a member of the batting team may be put out include the ground out, force out, and tag out.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] These occur either when a runner is forced to advance to a base, and a fielder with possession of the ball reaches that base before the runner does, or the runner is touched by the ball, held in a fielder's hand, while not on a base.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] (The batter-runner is always forced to advance to first base, and any other runners must advance to the next base if a teammate is forced to advance to their base.) It is possible to record two outs in the course of the same play.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Three outs in one play, a triple play, is possible, though rare.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Players put out or retired must leave the field, returning to their team's dugout or bench.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A runner may be stranded on base when a third out is recorded against another player on the team.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Stranded runners do not benefit the team in its next turn at bat as every half-inning begins with the bases empty.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] An individual player's turn batting or plate appearance is complete when the player reaches base, hits a home run, makes an out, or hits a ball that results in the team's third out, even if it is recorded against a teammate.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] On rare occasions, a batter may be at the plate when, without the batter's hitting the ball, a third out is recorded against a teammate—for instance, a runner getting caught stealing (tagged out attempting to steal a base).
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A batter with this sort of incomplete plate appearance starts off the team's next turn batting; any balls or strikes recorded against the batter the previous inning are erased.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A runner may circle the bases only once per plate appearance and thus can score at most a single run per batting turn.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Once a player has completed a plate appearance, that player may not bat again until the eight other members of the player's team have all taken their turn at bat in the batting order.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The batting order is set before the game begins, and may not be altered except for substitutions.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Once a player has been removed for a substitute, that player may not reenter the game.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Children's games often have more lenient rules, such as Little League rules, which allow players to be substituted back into the same game.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] If the designated hitter (DH) rule is in effect, each team has a tenth player whose sole responsibility is to bat (and run).
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The DH takes the place of another player—almost invariably the pitcher—in the batting order, but does not field.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Thus, even with the DH, each team still has a batting order of nine players and a fielding arrangement of nine players.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The number of players on a baseball roster, or *squad*, varies by league and by the level of organized play.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A Major League Baseball (MLB) team has a roster of 26 players with specific roles.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Most baseball leagues worldwide have the DH rule, including MLB, Japan's Pacific League, and Caribbean professional leagues, along with major American amateur organizations.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The Central League in Japan does not have the rule and high-level minor league clubs connected to National League teams are not required to field a DH.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In leagues that apply the designated hitter rule, a typical team has nine offensive regulars (including the DH), five starting pitchers, seven or eight relievers, a backup catcher, and two or three other reserve players.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The manager, or head coach, oversees the team's major strategic decisions, such as establishing the starting rotation, setting the lineup, or batting order, before each game, and making substitutions during games—in particular, bringing in relief pitchers.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches; they may have specialized responsibilities, such as working with players on hitting, fielding, pitching, or strength and conditioning.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] At most levels of organized play, two coaches are stationed on the field when the team is at bat: the first base coach and third base coach, who occupy designated coaches' boxes, just outside the foul lines.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] These coaches assist in the direction of baserunners, when the ball is in play, and relay tactical signals from the manager to batters and runners, during pauses in play.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In contrast to many other team sports, baseball managers and coaches generally wear their team's uniforms; coaches must be in uniform to be allowed on the field to confer with players during a game.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Any baseball game involves one or more umpires, who make rulings on the outcome of each play.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] At a minimum, one umpire will stand behind the catcher, to have a good view of the strike zone, and call balls and strikes.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Additional umpires may be stationed near the other bases, thus making it easier to judge plays such as attempted force outs and tag outs.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In MLB, four umpires are used for each game, one near each base.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In the playoffs, six umpires are used: one at each base and two in the outfield along the foul lines.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Many of the pre-game and in-game strategic decisions in baseball revolve around a fundamental fact: in general, right-handed batters tend to be more successful against left-handed pitchers and, to an even greater degree, left-handed batters tend to be more successful against right-handed pitchers.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A manager with several left-handed batters in the regular lineup, who knows the team will be facing a left-handed starting pitcher, may respond by starting one or more of the right-handed backups on the team's roster.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] During the late innings of a game, as relief pitchers and pinch hitters are brought in, the opposing managers will often go back and forth trying to create favorable matchups with their substitutions.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The manager of the fielding team trying to arrange same-handed pitcher-batter matchups and the manager of the batting team trying to arrange opposite-handed matchups.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] With a team that has the lead in the late innings, a manager may remove a starting position player—especially one whose turn at bat is not likely to come up again—for a more skillful fielder (known as a defensive substitution).
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The tactical decision that precedes almost every play in a baseball game involves pitch selection.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] By gripping and then releasing the baseball in a certain manner, and by throwing it at a certain speed, pitchers can cause the baseball to break to either side, or downward, as it approaches the batter, thus creating differing pitches that can be selected.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Among the resulting wide variety of pitches that may be thrown, the four basic types are the fastball, the changeup (or off-speed pitch), and two breaking balls—the curveball and the slider.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Pitchers have different repertoires of pitches they are skillful at throwing.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Conventionally, before each pitch, the catcher signals the pitcher what type of pitch to throw, as well as its general vertical or horizontal location.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] If there is disagreement on the selection, the pitcher may shake off the sign and the catcher will call for a different pitch.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] With a runner on base and taking a lead, the pitcher may attempt a pickoff, a quick throw to a fielder covering the base to keep the runner's lead in check or, optimally, effect a tag out.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Pickoff attempts, however, are subject to rules that severely restrict the pitcher's movements before and during the pickoff attempt.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Violation of any one of these rules could result in the umpire calling a balk against the pitcher, which permits any runners on base to advance one base with impunity.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] If an attempted stolen base is anticipated, the catcher may call for a pitchout, a ball thrown deliberately off the plate, allowing the catcher to catch it while standing and throw quickly to a base.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Facing a batter with a strong tendency to hit to one side of the field, the fielding team may employ a shift, with most or all of the fielders moving to the left or right of their usual positions.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] With a runner on third base, the infielders may play in, moving closer to home plate to improve the odds of throwing out the runner on a ground ball, though a sharply hit grounder is more likely to carry through a drawn-in infield.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Several basic offensive tactics come into play with a runner on first base, including the fundamental choice of whether to attempt a steal of second base.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The hit and run is sometimes employed, with a skillful contact hitter, the runner takes off with the pitch, drawing the shortstop or second baseman over to second base, creating a gap in the infield for the batter to poke the ball through.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The sacrifice bunt, calls for the batter to focus on making soft contact with the ball, so that it rolls a short distance into the infield, allowing the runner to advance into scoring position as the batter is thrown out at first.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A batter, particularly one who is a fast runner, may also attempt to bunt for a hit.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A sacrifice bunt employed with a runner on third base, aimed at bringing that runner home, is known as a squeeze play.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] With a runner on third and fewer than two outs, a batter may instead concentrate on hitting a fly ball that, even if it is caught, will be deep enough to allow the runner to tag up and score—a successful batter, in this case, gets credit for a sacrifice fly.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In order to increase the chance of advancing a batter to first base via a walk, the manager will sometimes signal a batter who is ahead in the count (i.e., has more balls than strikes) to take, or not swing at, the next pitch.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The batter's potential reward of reaching base (via a walk) exceeds the disadvantage if the next pitch is a strike.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Consensus once held that today's baseball is a North American development from the older game rounders, popular among children in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] American baseball historian David Block suggests that the game originated in England; recently uncovered historical evidence supports this position.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] According to Block and official MLB historian John Thorn, this earlier version of baseball may have involved hitting the ball with a hand, making it akin to today's punchball.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Block argues that rounders and early baseball were actually regional variants of each other, and that the game's most direct antecedents are the English games of stoolball and "tut-ball".
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The earliest known reference to baseball is in a 1744 British publication, *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book*, by John Newbery.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Base Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The first recorded baseball game in North America was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules, which in turn were based on rules developed in 1837 by William R.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The game then went on to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, with Americans backing the sport as a way to spread American values.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area, and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The American League evolved from the minor Western League, which was reorganized under Ban Johnson in 1893.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] It was not until 1901 that the American League was formally established as a major league.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] By 1893, crucial structural changes (like moving the pitching distance to 60 feet, 6 inches) firmly cemented the modern rulebook.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The first commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] This so-called "dead-ball era" ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Strict new regulations that governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Many minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Latin-American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Despite having been called "America's national pastime", baseball is well-established in several other countries.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] As early as 1877, a professional league, the International Association, featured teams from both Canada and the United States.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] While baseball is widely played in Canada and many minor league teams have been based in the country, the American major leagues did not include a Canadian club until 1969, when the Montreal Expos joined the National League as an expansion team.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 1977, the expansion Toronto Blue Jays joined the American League.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 1847, American soldiers played what may have been the first baseball game in Mexico at Parque Los Berros in Xalapa, Veracruz.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The first formal baseball league outside of the United States and Canada was founded in 1878 in Cuba, which maintains a rich baseball tradition.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The English football club, Aston Villa, were the first British baseball champions winning the 1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The 2025 National Champions were the London Mets.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The Dominican Republic held its first islandwide championship tournament in 1912.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Professional baseball tournaments and leagues began to form in other countries between the world wars, including the Netherlands (formed in 1922), Australia (1934), Japan (1936), Mexico (1937), and Puerto Rico (1938).
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The Japanese major leagues have long been considered the highest quality professional circuits outside of the United States.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] After World War II, professional leagues were founded in many Latin American countries, most prominently Venezuela (1946) and the Dominican Republic (1955).
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Since the early 1970s, the annual Caribbean Series has matched the championship clubs from the four leading Latin American winter leagues: the Dominican Professional Baseball League, Mexican Pacific League, Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League, and Venezuelan Professional Baseball League.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In Asia, South Korea (1982), Taiwan (1990) and China (2003) all have professional leagues.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Other European countries have seen professional leagues; the most successful, other than the Dutch league, is the Italian league, founded in 1948.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 2004, Australia won a surprise silver medal at the Olympic Games.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The Confédération Européene de Baseball (European Baseball Confederation), founded in 1953, organizes a number of competitions between clubs from different countries.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Women's baseball is played on an organized amateur basis in numerous countries.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] After being admitted to the Olympics as a medal sport beginning with the 1992 Games, baseball was dropped from the 2012 Summer Olympic Games at the 2005 International Olympic Committee meeting.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] While the sport's lack of a following in much of the world was a factor, more important was MLB's reluctance to allow its players to participate during the major league season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] MLB initiated the World Baseball Classic, scheduled to precede its season, partly as a replacement, high-profile international tournament.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The inaugural Classic, held in March 2006, was the first tournament involving national teams to feature a significant number of MLB participants.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The Baseball World Cup was discontinued after its 2011 edition in favor of an expanded World Baseball Classic.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Baseball has certain attributes that set it apart from the other popular team sports in the countries where it has a following.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] All of these sports use a clock, play is less individual, and the variation between playing fields is not as substantial or important.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The comparison between cricket and baseball demonstrates that many of baseball's distinctive elements are shared in various ways with similar sports.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In clock-limited sports, games often end with a team that holds the lead killing the clock rather than competing aggressively against the opposing team.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In contrast, baseball has no clock, thus a team cannot win without getting the last batter out and rallies are not constrained by time.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] At almost any turn in any baseball game, the most advantageous strategy is some form of aggressive strategy.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] While nine innings has been the standard since the beginning of professional baseball, the duration of the average major league game has increased steadily through the years.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, games typically took an hour and a half to play.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In the 1920s, they averaged just less than two hours, which eventually ballooned to 2:38 in 1960.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] By 1997, the average American League game lasted 2:57 (National League games were about 10 minutes shorter—pitchers at the plate making for quicker outs than designated hitters).
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 2004, Major League Baseball declared that its goal was an average game of 2:45.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] By 2014, though, the average MLB game took over three hours to complete.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The lengthening of games is attributed to longer breaks between half-innings for television commercials, increased offense, more pitching changes, and a slower pace of play, with pitchers taking more time between each delivery, and batters stepping out of the box more frequently.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Other leagues have experienced similar issues.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 2008, Nippon Professional Baseball took steps aimed at shortening games by 12 minutes from the preceding decade's average of 3:18.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 2016, the average nine-inning playoff game in Major League baseball was 3 hours and 35 minutes.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] This was up 10 minutes from 2015 and 21 minutes from 2014.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In response to the lengthening of the game, MLB decided from the 2023 season onward to institute a pitch clock rule to penalize batters and pitchers who take too much time between pitches; this had the effect of shortening 2023 regular season games by 24 minutes on average.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Although baseball is a team sport, individual players are often placed under scrutiny and pressure.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] While rewarding, it has sometimes been described as "ruthless" due to the pressure on the individual player.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] In 1915, a baseball instructional manual pointed out that every single pitch, of which there are often more than two hundred in a game, involves an individual, one-on-one contest: "the pitcher and the batter in a battle of wits".
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Pitcher, batter, and fielder all act essentially independent of each other.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] While coaching staffs can signal pitcher or batter to pursue certain tactics, the execution of the play itself is a series of solitary acts.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] If the batter hits a line drive, the outfielder is solely responsible for deciding to try to catch it or play it on the bounce and for succeeding or failing.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The statistical precision of baseball is both facilitated by this isolation and reinforces it.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] There is no statistical equivalent in cricket for the fielding error and thus less emphasis on personal responsibility in this area of play.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Unlike those of most sports, baseball playing fields can vary significantly in size and shape.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Major league teams often skirt even this rule.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] For example, at Daikin Park, which became the home of the Houston Astros in 2000, the Crawford Boxes in left field are only 315 feet (96 m) from home plate.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] There are no rules at all that address the height of fences or other structures at the edge of the outfield.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The most famously idiosyncratic outfield boundary is the left-field wall at Boston's Fenway Park, in use since 1912: the Green Monster is 310 feet (94 m) from home plate down the line and 37 feet (11 m) tall.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Similarly, there are no regulations at all concerning the dimensions of foul territory.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Thus a foul fly ball may be entirely out of play in a park with little space between the foul lines and the stands, but a foulout in a park with more expansive foul ground.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A fence in foul territory that is close to the outfield line will tend to direct balls that strike it back toward the fielders, while one that is farther away may actually prompt more collisions, as outfielders run full speed to field balls deep in the corner.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] These variations can make the difference between a double and a triple or inside-the-park home run.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The surface of the field is also unregulated.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] While the adjacent image shows a traditional field surfacing arrangement (and the one used by virtually all MLB teams with naturally surfaced fields), teams are free to decide what areas will be grassed or bare.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Some fields—including several in MLB—use artificial turf.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Surface variations can have a significant effect on how ground balls behave and are fielded as well as on baserunning.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Similarly, the presence of a roof (seven major league teams play in stadiums with permanent or retractable roofs) can greatly affect how fly balls are played.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] While football and soccer players deal with similar variations of field surface and stadium covering, the size and shape of their fields are much more standardized.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The area out-of-bounds on a football or soccer field does not affect play the way foul territory in baseball does, so variations in that regard are largely insignificant.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] These physical variations create a distinctive set of playing conditions at each ballpark.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Other local factors, such as altitude and climate, can also significantly affect play.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A given stadium may acquire a reputation as a pitcher's park or a hitter's park, if one or the other discipline notably benefits from its unique mix of elements.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The most exceptional park in this regard is Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Its high altitude—5,282 feet (1,610 m) above sea level—is partly responsible for giving it the strongest hitter's park effect in the major leagues due to the low air pressure.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs, is known for its fickle disposition: a pitcher's park when the strong winds off Lake Michigan are blowing in, it becomes more of a hitter's park when they are blowing out.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] The absence of a standardized field affects not only how particular games play out, but the nature of team rosters and players' statistical records.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] For example, hitting a fly ball 330 feet (100 m) into right field might result in an easy catch on the warning track at one park, and a home run at another.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] A team that plays in a park with a relatively short right field, such as the New York Yankees, will tend to stock its roster with left-handed pull hitters, who can best exploit it.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p01] On the individual level, a player who spends most of his career with a team that plays in a hitter's park will gain an advantage in batting statistics over time—even more so if his talents are especially suited to the park.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Organized baseball lends itself to statistics to a greater degree than many other sports.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Each play is discrete and has a relatively small number of possible outcomes.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The Official Baseball Rules administered by MLB require the official scorer to categorize each baseball play unambiguously.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The rules provide detailed criteria to promote consistency.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The score report is the official basis for both the box score of the game and the relevant statistical records.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] General managers, managers, and baseball scouts use statistics to evaluate players and make strategic decisions.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Certain traditional statistics are familiar to most baseball fans.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Among the many other statistics that are kept are those collectively known as *situational statistics*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] For example, statistics can indicate which specific pitchers a certain batter performs best against.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] If a given situation statistically favors a certain batter, the manager of the fielding team may be more likely to change pitchers or have the pitcher intentionally walk the batter in order to face one who is less likely to succeed.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Sabermetrics is the field of baseball statistical study and the development of new statistics and analytical tools.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Such new statistics are also called sabermetrics.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The term was coined around 1980 by one of the field's leading proponents, Bill James, and derives from the Society for American Baseball Research (SABR).
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as the national religion of the US.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] American influence in the Western Hemisphere has meant that baseball grew significantly in the region.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] A century later, the situation was very different.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most popular blue-collar-oriented American spectator sports.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] This led to baseball being granted the title of "America's favorite pastime" by many American baseball fans.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] As historians and scholars now speculate, baseball is a metaphor of the American way of life In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] After multiple years of declines since 2017, baseball attendance has grown slightly in recent years.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In 2024, attendance was 71.3 million, the highest since 2017.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball is very popular in Venezuela; in 2011, 95% of people surveyed claimed it to be the national sport.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In Nicaragua and Panama, baseball is also considered the national sport.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] While soccer is still more popular, baseball is a fast-growing sport in Mexico.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In 2024, top Mexican League baseball teams outdraw some Liga MX teams in attendance.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball also is somewhat popular in Colombia, though secondary to soccer, especially in coastal areas such as Barranquilla and Cartagena which are near the Caribbean.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In recent years, baseball has grown in popularity in Colombia, especially in the capital of Bogotá, due an increase of Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In Brazil, baseball fan popularity has grown in the last few years, thanks to MLB broadcasts in Brazilian ESPN and the historic silver medal in 2023 Pan-American games.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] However, it still lags behind basketball and American football in the list of most played sports in Brazil.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball has also grown in popularity in Argentina and Peru in recent years due to Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Costa Rica has also seen a growth in the popularity of baseball.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Since 1987, baseballs have exclusively been made in the Costa Rican town of Turrialba.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In recent years, Major leaguer Mauricio Dubón has made efforts to increase support for the sport in the country.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The sport's overall popularity in Latin America has assisted in integrating Latin American migrants to the United States.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport, the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball is also one of the most popular sports of Aruba and Curaçao, and a growing sport in The Bahamas and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In East Asia, baseball is among the most popular sports in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In Japan, where baseball is inarguably the leading spectator team sport, combined revenue for the twelve teams in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the body that oversees both the Central and Pacific Leagues, was estimated at $1 billion in 2007.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Total NPB attendance for the year was approximately 20 million.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] While in the preceding two decades, MLB attendance grew by 50 percent and revenue nearly tripled, the comparable NPB figures were stagnant.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] There are concerns that MLB's growing interest in acquiring star Japanese players will hurt the game in their home country.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Revenue figures are not released for the country's amateur system.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Similarly, according to one official pronouncement, the sport's governing authority "has never taken into account attendance ... because its greatest interest has always been the development of athletes".
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In Taiwan, baseball is one of the most widely spectated sports, in TV and person.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown significantly in China in recent years, with MLB estimating in 2019 that there are 21 million active fans in the country.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball was considered a national pastime in the Philippines in the 1960s and 70s, but the sport has since declined in popularity.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Since 2005, there have been efforts to revitalize the sport in the country.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball saw a surge in popularity in Thailand following the countries' silver medal in baseball in the 2025 SEA Games, which were hosted in Thailand.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball is generally a niche sport in Europe.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] However, baseball is somewhat popular in the Netherlands, where it is known as *honkbal*, thanks to influence from the United States after World War II and the Kingdoms control over Aruba and Curaçao where it is the most popular sport.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball is also somewhat popular in portions of Italy, especially in the town of Nettuno, due to influence from American soldiers after World War II.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown in recent years in the Czech Republic, due in part to the Czech teams' success in the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in Palau and Guam.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In Australia, baseball is a niche sport but the country does have a professional league.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Because the league is played in winter for the western hemisphere, it attracts American and Korean professional players looking to play winter league baseball.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In 2026, there were more than 30 Australians playing college baseball in the United States compared to six in 2020.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The Dodgers operate a large baseball academy in Mpigi, Uganda, and there are also baseball programs in Luwero, Uganda.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] There is also a Africa Baseball Academy in Nairobi, Nigeria.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball was popular in South Africa prior to World War 2 but popularity has since waned.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] There are still teams and attempts to raise the popularity of baseball in the country, including the introduction of Baseball5.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] There is a growing baseball program in South Sudan, which has resulted in professional contracts.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The Japan-Africa Baseball & Softball Foundation has created Koshien high school baseball tournaments in Tanzania, Ghana and Kenya, which Tanzania being the most successful.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] There are further plans for similar tournaments in Nigeria, South Sudan, Benin, Cameroon and Zambia.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] As of 2024, Little League Baseball oversees leagues with 2 million participants in more than 80 countries.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The number of players has fallen since the 1990s, when 3 million children took part in Little League Baseball annually.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Babe Ruth League teams have over 1 million participants.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] According to the president of the International Baseball Federation in 2009, between 300,000 and 500,000 women and girls play baseball around the world, including Little League and the introductory game of Tee Ball.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] A varsity baseball team is an established part of physical education departments at most high schools and colleges in the United States.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In 2015, nearly half a million high schoolers and over 34,000 collegians played on their schools' baseball teams.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] By early in the 20th century, intercollegiate baseball was Japan's leading sport.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Today, high school baseball in particular is immensely popular there.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The final rounds of the two annual tournaments—the National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament in the spring, and the even more important National High School Baseball Championship in the summer—are broadcast around the country.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The tournaments are known, respectively, as Spring Koshien and Summer Koshien after the 55,000-capacity stadium where they are played.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In Cuba, baseball is a mandatory part of the state system of physical education, which begins at age six.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Talented children as young as seven are sent to special district schools for more intensive training—the first step on a ladder whose acme is the national baseball team.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the United States and elsewhere.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Dozens of English-language idioms have been derived from baseball; in particular, the game is the source of a number of widely used sexual euphemisms.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The first networked radio broadcasts in North America were of the 1922 World Series: famed sportswriter Grantland Rice announced play-by-play from New York City's Polo Grounds on WJZ–Newark, New Jersey, which was connected by wire to WGY–Schenectady, New York, and WBZ–Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The baseball cap has become a ubiquitous fashion item not only in the United States and Japan, but also in countries where the sport itself is not particularly popular, such as the United Kingdom.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball has inspired many works of art and entertainment.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] There have been many baseball movies, including the Academy Award–winning *The Pride of the Yankees* (1942) and the Oscar nominees *The Natural* (1984) and *Field of Dreams* (1989).
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The American Film Institute's selection of the ten best sports movies includes *The Pride of the Yankees* at number 3 and *Bull Durham* (1988) at number 5.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball has provided thematic material for hits on both stage—the Adler–Ross musical *Damn Yankees*—and record—George J.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Gaskin's "Slide, Kelly, Slide", Simon and Garfunkel's "Mrs.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Robinson", and John Fogerty's "Centerfield".
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The baseball-inspired comedic sketch "Who's on First?", popularized by Abbott and Costello in 1938, quickly became famous; six decades later, *Time* named it the best comedy routine of the 20th century.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Literary works connected to the game include the short fiction of Ring Lardner and novels such as Bernard Malamud's *The Natural* (the source for the movie), Robert Coover's *The Universal Baseball Association, Inc., J.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Henry Waugh, Prop.*, John Grisham's Calico Joe and W.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Kinsella's *Shoeless Joe* (the source for *Field of Dreams*).
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball's literary canon also includes the beat reportage of Damon Runyon; the columns of Grantland Rice, Red Smith, Dick Young, and Peter Gammons; and the essays of Roger Angell.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Among the celebrated nonfiction books in the field are Lawrence S.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Ritter's *The Glory of Their Times*, Roger Kahn's *The Boys of Summer*, and Michael Lewis's *Moneyball*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The 1970 publication of major league pitcher Jim Bouton's tell-all chronicle *Ball Four* is considered a turning point in the reporting of professional sports.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball has also inspired the creation of new cultural forms.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball cards were introduced in the late 19th century as trade cards.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] A typical example featured an image of a baseball player on one side and advertising for a business on the other.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In the early 1900s they were produced widely as promotional items by tobacco and confectionery companies.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The 1930s saw the popularization of the modern style of baseball card, with a player photograph accompanied on the rear by statistics and biographical data.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Baseball cards—many of which are now prized collectibles—are the source of the much broader trading card industry, involving similar products for different sports and non-sports-related fields.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Modern fantasy sports began in 1980 with the invention of Rotisserie League Baseball by New York writer Daniel Okrent and several friends.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Participants in a Rotisserie league draft notional teams from the list of active MLB players and play out an entire imaginary season with game outcomes based on the players' latest real-world statistics.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Rotisserie-style play quickly became a phenomenon.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Now known more generically as fantasy baseball, it has inspired similar games based on an array of different sports.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The field boomed with increasing Internet access and new fantasy sports-related websites.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] By 2008, 29.9 million people in the United States and Canada were playing fantasy sports, spending $800 million on the hobby.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The burgeoning popularity of fantasy baseball is also credited with the increasing attention paid to sabermetrics—first among fans, only later among baseball professionals.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Informal variations of baseball have popped up over time, with games like corkball reflecting local traditions and allowing the game to be played in diverse environments.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Two variations of baseball, softball and Baseball5, are internationally governed alongside baseball by the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] American professional baseball teams toured Britain in 1874 and 1889, and had a great effect on similar sports in Britain.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] In Wales and Merseyside, a strong community game had already developed with skills and plays more in keeping with the American game and the Welsh began to informally adopt the name "baseball" (Pêl Fas), to reflect the American style.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] By the 1890s, calls were made to follow the success of other working class sports (like Rugby in Wales and Soccer in Merseyside) and adopt a distinct set of rules and bureaucracy.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] During the 1892 season rules for the game of "baseball" were agreed and the game was officially codified.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] Finnish baseball, also known as pesäpallo, is a combination of traditional ball-batting team games and North American baseball, invented by Lauri "Tahko" Pihkala in the 1920s.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] The basic idea of pesäpallo is similar to that of baseball: the offense tries to score by hitting the ball successfully and running through the bases, while the defense tries to put the batter and runners out.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] One of the most important differences between pesäpallo and baseball is that the ball is pitched vertically, which makes hitting the ball, as well as controlling the power and direction of the hit, much easier.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-p02] This gives the offensive game more variety, speed, and tactical aspects compared to baseball.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus-internet-baseball-awards] The annual Greg Spira Memorial **Internet Baseball Awards** (IBA) are based on fan voting.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus-internet-baseball-awards] They were founded in 1991 by Greg Spira with the Most Valuable Player, Cy Young (now Pitcher of the Year), and Rookie of the Year awards, in each of the two leagues in Major League Baseball.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus-internet-baseball-awards] In 1998, an award for Manager of the Year was added in each league.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus-internet-baseball-awards] Spira managed the awards until his death at the end of 2011.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus-internet-baseball-awards] The awards were then named in his memory.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus-internet-baseball-awards] Since 1998, eight awards have been given each year.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus-internet-baseball-awards] From 1991 to 1997, there were six awards each year.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus has originated several popular new statistical tools that have become hallmarks of baseball analysis.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus is accredited by the Baseball Writers' Association of America.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Four of Baseball Prospectus's current regular writers are members of the Baseball Writers' Association of America and thus eligible to vote for nominees for Major League Baseball's post-season awards and the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus is formally an entity of Prospectus Entertainment Ventures, LLC, a private corporation that runs websites and publishes books focusing on the statistical analysis of the sports of baseball, basketball, and ice hockey.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] As of August 2014, the President & CEO is Joe Hamrahi, and Vice President is Dave Pease.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] For several years, Prospectus Entertainment Ventures (*PEV*) partnered with Football Outsiders for the publication and promotion of *Football Outsiders Almanac* (ISBN 1-4486-4845-9), before 2009 called *Pro Football Prospectus* (ISBN 0-452-28847-9).
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] On October 10, 2007, PEV launched *Basketball Prospectus,* a new website for the analysis of men's college and pro basketball, with Joe Sheehan taking the role of Managing Editor and announcing the lineup of principal writer-analysts for the site.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Initially, this website did not require a subscription for access, but it introduced subscriptions in 2011 for access to most of the material on the site.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] *BasketballProspectus.com*'s first annual book, *College Basketball Prospectus 2008–2009* (ISBN 0-452-28987-4), was published in October 2008.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] It released *Pro Basketball Prospectus 2009–10* for purchase online in October 2009.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Subsequently, it published both *College Basketball Prospectus 2010–11* (ISBN 1-4538-7282-5) and *Pro Basketball Prospectus 2010–11* (ISBN 1-4538-6899-2) in both print and online (PDF) modes.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] On March 19, 2008, Imagine Sports announced a strategic partnership with PEV and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Imagine sports owns the baseball simulation engine "Diamond Mind Baseball".
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] On October 14, 2008, PEV announced the acquisition of *Baseball Digest Daily* (BDD), an online blog devoted to baseball analysis and statistics.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Joe Hamrahi, new Chief Financial Officer of PEV and founder of BDD, reported that "PEV's decision to acquire Baseball Digest Daily further enhances the content offerings of Baseball Prospectus by adding some of the game's best analysts as well as over 100 pages of baseball news and original content.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] In addition, BDD's player tracker provides a platform for serious fans and fantasy baseball enthusiasts to easily monitor the progress of their teams, allowing users to manipulate and track the progress of an unlimited set of players over a customized period of time".
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] On February 23, 2009, Prospectus Entertainment Ventures (PEV) launched the website *Puck Prospectus* with the intent of providing cutting-edge analysis of hockey.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Will Carroll assumed the role of the Executive Editor, and Andrew Rothstein, the founder of *Puck Prospectus*, assumed the role of the Managing Editor.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Puck Prospectus published its first annual book, *Puck Prospectus 2010–2011* (ISBN 1-4538-1784-0) in both online and print formats.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Initially a free site, *Puck Prospectus* introduced subscriptions in 2011.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] On March 24, 2009, Baseball Prospectus announced that Nate Silver was stepping down as its Managing Partner, and Kevin Goldstein was assuming this role.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] At that time, PEV relinquished its previously announced financial interest in Silver's *FiveThirtyEight* blog.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] At the same time, it was announced that BP has a partnership relationship with ESPN.com.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] In January 2010, PEV's Managing Partner Kevin Goldstein reported that one of BP's founding members, Joe Sheehan, had departed the organization.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] He reported that John Perrotto had been elevated to full-time status on the BP staff and would become the new Editor-in-Chief of *BaseballProspectus.com*, taking over that responsibility from Christina Kahrl.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] And he reported that Jeff Euston was joining the BP staff and that Euston's *Cot's Baseball Contracts* website would be joining the Baseball Prospectus family.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] In February 2011, Perrotto was replaced as Editor-in-Chief by Steven Goldman.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] In February 2010, BP's "Fantasy Manager" Marc Normandin announced that BP had established a partnership with *Heater Magazine.* *Heater Magazine* ceased publication after the 2010 season.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] In November 2011, Kevin Goldstein announced that he was stepping down as PEV's Managing Partner in favor of Joe Hamrahi.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] On March 3, 2012, Hamrahi announced that Steven Goldman was stepping down as Editor-in-Chief of BaseballProspectus.com; Goldman had taken a position as a lead baseball writer for *Bleacher Report*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Ben Lindbergh was named Managing Editor of Baseball Prospectus on March 5, 2012 and Editor-in-Chief of Baseball Prospectus on July 13, 2012.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] On April 30, 2012, PEV's Managing Partner Joe Hamrahi announced that "Dan Brooks, Harry Pavlidis, and Brooks Baseball have agreed to team up and join forces with Baseball Prospectus.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] BrooksBaseball.net is the premier site for PITCHf/x analysis and pitch classification".
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] On March 15, 2013, after explaining a week earlier that its key staff of writers had been hired away by ESPN, Baseball Prospectus's Dave Pease declared in response to a question in the comments: "Basketball Prospectus will not be publishing any new content.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] On March 8, Pease had written: "You've probably noticed our Basketball Prospectus Premium coverage has been pretty quiet lately.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] You may have also noticed that our core pro writers, Kevin Pelton, Bradford Doolittle, and John Gasaway are now writing for ESPN Insider on a regular basis.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Late last year, we learned that, following their completion of the Pro Basketball Prospectus 2012–13 and College Basketball Prospectus 2012–13 annuals, Kevin, Bradford, and John would be moving to ESPN on a full-time basis".
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus was founded in 1996 by Gary Huckabay, who recruited the initial contributor group of Clay Davenport, Rany Jazayerli, Christina Kahrl, and Joe Sheehan, with the publication of the first annual set of forecasts.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] "That first year, BP charged $20 for a statistics guide produced on a photocopier.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] It printed around 300 copies and sold about 170 to fellow statheads, even though the book was missing the St.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] 'It was terrible,' recalls Kahrl, 'but it nevertheless didn't discourage us.' Within a few years Brassey's Inc. published the guide, which grew to about 3,000 copies.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] The kind of sabermetric approach favored by Baseball Prospectus has gained significant acceptance by the management of many Major League Baseball clubs, notably the Boston Red Sox and Cleveland Indians.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] BP has often been considered the modern successor to Bill James' *Baseball Abstract* series of books in the 1980s.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Reflecting its legacy as a group of sabermetricians who met over the Internet, BP has no "main office." Working for BP is a second or part-time job for many of the regular staff, who conduct their work for BP in their own home offices.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] The website *BaseballProspectus.com* began in 1997 primarily as a way to present original sabermetric research; publish advanced baseball statistics such as EqA, the Davenport Translations (DT's), and VORP; and promote sales of the annual book.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Beginning in 2003, the site placed most of its new articles, its PECOTA forecasts, and some of its statistical databases in a "premium" section that could be accessed only by subscription.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] However, in May 2011, BP "announced it has made its entire archive of premium and fantasy content over one year old completely and permanently free to the public".
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Until 2007, when the site began to post general advertising, the premium subscriptions and book sales were Baseball Prospectus' main source of revenues.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus does not publish a financial report or information about its subscriber base, but it appears to have used its income to expand its breadth of coverage, and it has not increased its subscription prices since initiating its premium service.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] It also offers a subscription to those interested in fantasy baseball, at a lower price than the premium subscriptions and giving access to fewer features and articles.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Given the competing career opportunities for some of BP's best-known and most statistics-savvy analysts, maintaining a fresh supply of sabermetrically sophisticated writers remains a challenge.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] At least three new regular BP writers (winner Ken Funck, Tim Kniker, and Matt Swartz) were discovered through this *Prospectus Idol* contest.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] In addition, BP had added Eric Seidman to its staff early in 2009 and then acquired Russell Carleton ("Pizza Cutter") and Colin Wyers in December 2009 to bolster its coverage of technical sabermetric issues.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] As late as the Fall of 2008, Seidman, Swartz, Carleton, Wyers, Daniel Novick and BP Idol finalist Brian Cartwright made up the entire staff of "Statistically Speaking" aka StatSpeak at MVN.com.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Carleton left the BP staff in May 2010, but returned in July 2012.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Seidman and Swartz left in February 2011.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Wyers was hired away by the Houston Astros in October 2013.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] In the press release announcing his hire, Jeff Luhnow noted, "Colin Wyers is a brilliant man with lots of well thought-out, practical, ideas.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] He is insuring the financial security of this company for years to come.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Oh yes, and his personal hygiene is above reproach".
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] So teams court them as part of their effort to win games".
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] By the beginning of the 2011 baseball season, none of BP's founders was an active contributor to the website or publications, though some of their earlier articles were included in two *Best of Baseball Prospectus* compendia that were published in 2011.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus writers promote several theories on proper baseball management and analysis, many of which are contrary to those of conventional baseball wisdom.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus researchers have concluded that there is no repeatable ability of clutch hitting.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] In an article published in 2006, Nate Silver argued that clutch hitting ability does exist to a degree.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] He argued that although not as important as traditional baseball analysis would suggest, clutch hitting ability was more significant than other sabermetric studies had shown.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] The article also found there to be a connection between clutch hitting ability and situational hitting, or the ability to adjust a hitting approach to fit the given situation.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus writers often successfully argue that traditional baseball statistics such as RBIs, wins, and batting average are poor reflections of a player's true contributions.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] For example, they have argued that RBIs are too dependent on factors outside of the player's control, namely the production of other hitters in the lineup.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] They similarly argue that wins are too affected by factors such as the team's offense and bullpen.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus writers assert that teams are typically inefficient in their use of their best relievers.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Teams typically assign their most effective reliever to the position of closer, using him in only save situations.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] According to many Baseball Prospectus writers, a team's best reliever should be used when the opposing team has its best chance at increasing its chances of winning.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Many writers argue that the sacrifice bunt and stolen base are overused in baseball.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Teams will often attempt these plays when the score is close.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Writers for Baseball Prospectus often argue that teams are, on average, actually lowering their expected number of runs scored.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] They argue that stolen base attempts are not completed frequently enough for them to be beneficial to the offense.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] For sacrifice bunts, they argue that the team is giving up more by sacrificing an out than they gain by advancing a runner one base.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Their thinking is derived from the grid of expected runs in an inning based on the outs and runner situation, which shows that the sacrifice is detrimental to a team given average players in most of the situations in which it is typically used.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] In a series of articles in 2004, James Click argued that sacrifice bunts are beneficial in some situations, dependent on the quality of the batter at the plate and the situation in the game.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus writers use a wide variety of sabermetric tools.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Voros McCracken's pathbreaking article on Defense Independent Pitching Statistics also first appeared on the BP website.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus, as well as other sabermetric analysts, are criticized for taking the human aspect out of the game of baseball.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Nate Silver, BP's Managing Partner at the time, responded to this criticism in "An Open Letter to Murray Chass," including offering to meet Chass to watch a ballgame.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Silver expounded on the case for a positive impact of sabermetrics on the game of baseball in an article "How Sabermetrics Helps Build a Better Ballgame," published on *Baseball Analysts.com*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Another type of criticism comes from those who believe that by broadening its coverage and audience, Baseball Prospectus is becoming more like the mainstream media and losing what made it unique.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Baseball Prospectus was widely criticized for publishing and aggressively promoting a 2003 story claiming that banished player/manager Pete Rose had reached an agreement to return to baseball.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Will Carroll made the rounds on television and radio, claiming to have spoken to unnamed sources who had actually seen the agreement.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] Spokesmen for both Rose and Major League Baseball refuted the claim, but Carroll and his colleagues insisted their reporting was accurate.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] No other news source confirmed the story.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-prospectus] In fact, Rose was not reinstated and remains banned from baseball.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The **Baseball Writers' Association of America** (**BBWAA**) is a professional association for journalists writing about Major League Baseball for daily newspapers, magazines, and qualifying websites.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The organization was founded in 1908 and is known for its annual awards and voting on membership in the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The organization began with 43 founding members.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Jackson, who became the association's first president.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] At that time, Jackson was the sporting editor (today called *sports editor*) of the *Detroit Free Press*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Also selected as officers were Irving E.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Sanborn of the *Chicago Tribune*, syndicated columnist Hugh Fullerton, and *The Boston Globe* baseball writer Tim Murnane.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] A second meeting was held in New York City in December; Sanborn decided he could not serve as an officer at that time, and he was replaced by William Weart of the *Philadelphia Times*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The slate of officers was ratified, and anyone who wrote about baseball in major league cities was eligible for membership.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] This policy changed, however, in December 1913, at which time it was decided that minor-league baseball writers could also become members.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Then, Jackson became a dominant force in the early years of the baseball writers, being elected as president of the association during nine consecutive terms.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Jackson finally retired in 1919, while Sanborn returned to assume the position of president.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] After that, Jackson became a member of the BBWAA Board of Directors.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The organization's primary function is to work with Major League Baseball and individual teams to assure clubhouse and press-box access for BBWAA members.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] In addition, BBWAA members also elect players to the National Baseball Hall of Fame, which is the organization's most public function.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] All writers with 10 continuous years of membership in the BBWAA, plus active BBWAA membership at any time in the preceding 10 years, are eligible to vote for the Hall of Fame.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The BBWAA also votes annually for the Most Valuable Player Award, Cy Young Award, Jackie Robinson Rookie of the Year Award, and Manager of the Year Award in each of the two major leagues.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The Hall of Fame also empowers the BBWAA's Historical Overview Committee, made up of 11 or 12 veteran BBWAA members, to formulate the annual ballot for the Veterans Committee.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Considering the ready availability of television broadcasts for the majority of baseball games, plus instant access to information through the Internet, some have called into question why the BBWAA has not broadened its membership rules to include broadcasters and researchers.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Others have openly questioned why the BBWAA is involved in the award and Hall of Fame voting processes at all, citing in some cases journalistic integrity and the need to remain unbiased in their coverage of newsworthy events.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The BBWAA's most public function is to annually vote on candidates for the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] In or about 2000, the BBWAA took over the voting responsibility for the Edgar Martínez Award, given each year to the outstanding designated hitter in the American League.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] From 1953 to 1962, the BBWAA presented a "Sophomore of the Year Award" in each league.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] In 1997, a 36-member BBWAA panel selected the Major League Baseball All-Time Team.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The annual BBWAA Career Excellence Award is the highest award given by the BBWAA.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Taylor Spink, longtime publisher of *The Sporting News*, it was named the J.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Taylor Spink Award until adopting its current name in February 2021.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] It has been awarded annually for "meritorious contributions to baseball writing", except for one year during the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Recipients are not considered members of the National Baseball Hall of Fame but are permanently recognized in an exhibit at the Hall's library.
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] For information about the chapter and its presiding officer, see footnote and Red Foley (past chairman).
[src:baseball-prospectus/baseball-writers-association-of-america] For a list of presidents and secretaries from 1908 to the present, see footnote During the 2012 World Series, the Association elected its first female president, Susan Slusser, of the *San Francisco Chronicle*.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Players advance the ball by bouncing it while walking or running (dribbling) or by passing it to a teammate, both of which require considerable skill.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] On offense, players may use a variety of shots – the layup, the jump shot, or a dunk.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] On defense, they may steal the ball from a dribbler, intercept passes, or block shots.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Either offense, or defense may collect a rebound, which is a missed shot that bounces from rim or backboard.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] It is a violation to lift or drag one's pivot foot without dribbling the ball, to carry it, or to hold the ball with both hands then resume dribbling.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The five players on each side fall into five playing positions.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The tallest player is typically the center, the second-tallest and strongest is the power forward.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The small forward is a shorter, but very agile player.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Lastly, the shortest players or the best ball handlers are the shooting guard and the point guard.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] These players implement the coach's game plan by managing the execution of offensive and defensive plays (player positioning).
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Informally, players may play three-on-three, two-on-two, and one-on-one.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Invented in 1891 by Canadian-American gym teacher James Naismith in Springfield, Massachusetts, in the United States, basketball has evolved to become one of the world's most popular and widely viewed sports.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The National Basketball Association (NBA) is the most significant professional basketball league in the world in terms of popularity, salaries, talent, and level of competition (drawing most of its talent from U.S. college basketball).
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Outside North America, the top clubs from national leagues qualify to continental championships such as the EuroLeague and the Basketball Champions League Americas.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The FIBA Basketball World Cup and Men's Olympic Basketball Tournament are the major international events of the sport and attract top national teams from around the world.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Each continent hosts regional competitions for national teams, like EuroBasket and FIBA AmeriCup.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The FIBA Women's Basketball World Cup and women's Olympic basketball tournament feature top national teams from continental championships.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The main North American league is the WNBA (NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Championship is also popular), whereas the strongest European clubs participate in the EuroLeague Women.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] In December 1891, James Naismith, a Canadian-American professor of physical education and instructor at the International Young Men's Christian Association Training School (now Springfield College) in Springfield, Massachusetts, was trying to keep his gym class active on a rainy day.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] He sought a vigorous indoor game to keep his students occupied and at proper levels of fitness during the long New England winters.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] After rejecting other ideas as either too rough or poorly suited to walled-in gymnasiums, he invented a new game in which players would pass a ball to teammates and try to score points by tossing the ball into a basket mounted on a wall.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Naismith wrote the basic rules and nailed a peach basket onto an elevated track.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Naismith initially set up the peach basket with its bottom intact, which meant that the ball had to be retrieved manually after each "basket" or point scored.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] This quickly proved tedious, so Naismith removed the bottom of the basket to allow the balls to be poked out with a long dowel after each scored basket.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Shortly after, Senda Berenson, instructor of physical culture at the nearby Smith College, went to Naismith to learn more about the game.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Fascinated by the new sport and the values it could teach, she started to organize games with her pupils, following adjusted rules.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The first official women's interinstitutional game was played barely 11 months later, between the University of California and Miss Head's School.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] In 1899, a committee was established at the Conference of Physical Training in Springfield to draw up general rules for women's basketball.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Thus, the sport quickly spread throughout America's schools, colleges and universities with uniform rules for both sexes.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Basketball was originally played with a soccer ball.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] These round balls from "association football" were made, at the time, with a set of laces to close off the hole needed for inserting the inflatable bladder after the other sewn-together segments of the ball's cover had been flipped outside-in.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] These laces could cause bounce passes and dribbling to be unpredictable.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Eventually a lace-free ball construction method was invented, and this change to the game was endorsed by Naismith (whereas in American football, the lace construction proved to be advantageous for gripping and remains to this day).
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The first balls made specifically for basketball were brown, and it was only in the late 1950s that Tony Hinkle, searching for a ball that would be more visible to players and spectators alike, introduced the orange ball that is now in common use.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Dribbling was not part of the original game except for the "bounce pass" to teammates.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Passing the ball was the primary means of ball movement.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Dribbling was eventually introduced but limited by the asymmetric shape of early balls.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Dribbling was common by 1896, with a rule against the double dribble by 1898.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The peach baskets were used until 1906 when they were finally replaced by metal hoops with backboards.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] A further change was soon made, so the ball merely passed through.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Whenever a person got the ball in the basket, their team would gain a point.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Whichever team got the most points won the game.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The baskets were originally nailed to the mezzanine balcony of the playing court, but this proved impractical when spectators in the balcony began to interfere with shots.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The backboard was introduced to prevent this interference; it had the additional effect of allowing rebound shots.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Naismith's handwritten diaries, discovered by his granddaughter in early 2006, indicate that he was nervous about the new game he had invented, which incorporated rules from a children's game called duck on a rock, as many had failed before it.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Frank Mahan, one of the players from the original first game, approached Naismith after the Christmas break, in early 1892, asking him what he intended to call his new game.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Naismith replied that he had not thought of it because he had been focused on just getting the game started.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Mahan suggested that it be called "Naismith ball", at which he laughed, saying that a name like that would kill any game.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Mahan then said, "Why not call it basketball?" Naismith replied, "We have a basket and a ball, and it seems to me that would be a good name for it." The first official game was played in the YMCA gymnasium in Albany, New York, on January 20, 1892, with nine players.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The game ended at 1–0; the shot was made from 25 feet (7.6 m), on a court just half the size of a present-day Streetball or National Basketball Association (NBA) court.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] At the time, soccer was being played with 10 to a team (which was increased to 11).
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] When winter weather got too icy to play soccer, teams were taken indoors, and it was convenient to have them split in half and play basketball with five on each side.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] By 1897–98, teams of five became standard.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Basketball's early adherents were dispatched to YMCAs throughout the United States, and it quickly spread through the United States and Canada.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] By 1895, it was well established at several women's high schools.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] While YMCA was responsible for initially developing and spreading the game, within a decade it discouraged the new sport, as rough play and rowdy crowds began to detract from YMCA's primary mission.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] However, other amateur sports clubs, colleges, and professional clubs quickly filled the void.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] In the years before World War I, the Amateur Athletic Union and the Intercollegiate Athletic Association of the United States (forerunner of the NCAA) vied for control over the rules for the game.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The first pro league, the National Basketball League, was formed in 1898 to protect players from exploitation and to promote a less rough game.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] James Naismith was instrumental in establishing college basketball.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Beamis fielded the first college basketball team just a year after the Springfield YMCA game at the suburban Pittsburgh Geneva College.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Naismith himself later coached at the University of Kansas for six years, before handing the reins to renowned coach Forrest "Phog" Allen.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Naismith's disciple Amos Alonzo Stagg brought basketball to the University of Chicago, while Adolph Rupp, a student of Naismith's at Kansas, enjoyed great success as coach at the University of Kentucky.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] On February 9, 1895, the first intercollegiate 5-on-5 game was played at Hamline University between Hamline and the School of Agriculture, which was affiliated with the University of Minnesota.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The School of Agriculture won in a 9–3 game.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] In 1901, colleges, including the University of Chicago, Columbia University, Cornell University, Dartmouth College, the University of Minnesota, the U.S.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Naval Academy, the University of Colorado and Yale University began sponsoring men's games.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] In 1905, frequent injuries on the football field prompted President Theodore Roosevelt to suggest that colleges form a governing body, resulting in the creation of the Intercollegiate Athletic Association of the United States (IAAUS).
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] In 1910, that body changed its name to the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA).
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The first Canadian interuniversity basketball game was played at YMCA in Kingston, Ontario on February 6, 1904, when McGill University – Naismith's alma mater – visited Queen's University.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] McGill won 9–7 in overtime; the score was 7–7 at the end of regulation play, and a ten-minute overtime period settled the outcome.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] A good turnout of spectators watched the game.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The first men's national championship tournament, the National Association of Intercollegiate Basketball tournament, which still exists as the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA) tournament, was organized in 1937.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The first national championship for NCAA teams, the National Invitation Tournament (NIT) in New York, was organized in 1938; the NCAA national tournament began one year later.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] College basketball was rocked by gambling scandals from 1948 to 1951, when dozens of players from top teams were implicated in game-fixing and point shaving.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Partially spurred by an association with cheating, the NIT lost support to the NCAA tournament.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Before widespread school district consolidation, most American high schools were far smaller than their present-day counterparts.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] During the first decades of the 20th century, basketball quickly became the ideal interscholastic sport due to its modest equipment and personnel requirements.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] In the days before widespread television coverage of professional and college sports, the popularity of high school basketball was unrivaled in many parts of America.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Perhaps the most legendary of high school teams was Indiana's Franklin Wonder Five, which took the nation by storm during the 1920s, dominating Indiana basketball and earning national recognition.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Today virtually every high school in the United States fields a basketball team in varsity competition.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Basketball's popularity remains high, both in rural areas where they carry the identification of the entire community, as well as at some larger schools known for their basketball teams where many players go on to participate at higher levels of competition after graduation.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] In the 2016–17 season, 980,673 boys and girls represented their schools in interscholastic basketball competition, according to the National Federation of State High School Associations.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The states of Illinois, Indiana, and Kentucky are particularly well known for their residents' devotion to high school basketball, commonly called Hoosier Hysteria in Indiana; the critically acclaimed film *Hoosiers* shows high school basketball's depth of meaning to these communities.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] ⁣There is currently no tournament to determine a national high school champion.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The most serious effort was the National Interscholastic Basketball Tournament at the University of Chicago from 1917 to 1930.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The event was organized by Amos Alonzo Stagg and sent invitations to state champion teams.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The tournament started out as a mostly Midwest affair but grew.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Faced with opposition from the National Federation of State High School Associations and North Central Association of Colleges and Schools that bore a threat of the schools losing their accreditation the last tournament was in 1930.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The organizations said they were concerned that the tournament was being used to recruit professional players from the prep ranks.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The tournament did not invite minority schools or private/parochial schools.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The National Catholic Interscholastic Basketball Tournament ran from 1924 to 1941 at Loyola University.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The National Catholic Invitational Basketball Tournament from 1954 to 1978 played at a series of venues, including Catholic University, Georgetown and George Mason.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The National Interscholastic Basketball Tournament for Black High Schools was held from 1929 to 1942 at Hampton Institute.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] The National Invitational Interscholastic Basketball Tournament was held from 1941 to 1967 starting out at Tuskegee Institute.
[src:baseball-prospectus/basketball-p01] Following a pause during World War II it resumed at Tennessee State College in Nashville.
